http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/18947464/&cid=1116756580&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Woods-Mickelson rivalry begins to re-emerge - Golf - MSNBC.com Woods-Mickelson rivalry begins to re-emerge 'Heâ€™s playing better, no doubt about that,' Tiger says of Lefty Matt Sullivan / Reuters Tiger Woods celebrates afterÂ holing anÂ eagle from the fairway of the 18th hole during the Pro-Am of the Memorial Tournament on Wednesday. DUBLIN, Ohio - Tiger Woods and Jack Nicklaus were side by side on the practice range Wednesday, the two most prolific major champions in golf who looked nothing alike except for the sweat pouring off their faces on a steamy day at Muirfield Village. Nicklaus was warming up for the pro-am, the closest he gets to competition these days. Woods was shaking off rust as he tries to win for the fourth time this year, with one eye on the U.S. Open in two weeks. There are amazing parallels in their careers, from green jackets at Augusta National to the two claret jugs at St. Andrews. They were the youngest of their eras to complete the career Grand Slam. Both were 30 when their fathers died, and both went on to win the British Open that summer. Perhaps the most glaring difference was their rivals. Nicklaus had rivals with staying power that stretched over two decades, from Arnold Palmer to Gary Player, Lee Trevino to Tom Watson. Woodsâ€™ rivals seem to come and go like fashion trends â€” David Duval in 1999, Phil Mickelson in 2001, Ernie Els in 2002, Vijay Singh in 2004, nobody in 2000. After his pro-am round at the Memorial, Woods recalled talking to Nicklaus about rivalries. â€œHe said that as long as youâ€™re part of the conversation over 20 years,â€ Woods said with a smile, â€œthen youâ€™re doing all right.â€ Mickelson has joined the conversation again. A week after Woods won the Wachovia Championship, Mickelson won The Players Championship. They are 1-2 in the world ranking and on the PGA Tour money list. Both return to action this week at the Memorial, which has a 107-man field with the focus squarely on two players. â€œHeâ€™s playing better, no doubt about that,â€ Woods said. Mickelson has 31 victories on the PGA Tour â€” no one has more among active players except Woods â€” and now is working with Butch Harmon, the celebrated swing coach who refined and then retooled Woodsâ€™ swing at the start of his career. Of all the rivalries Woods has faced, this is the most natural, even he says that his biggest rival is himself. Slide show: Week in Sports Pictures Week in Sports Pictures Sports fans riot and show their elfin side, while flips, turns and wipeouts punctuate motor sports this week. â€œI keep pushing myself pretty hard regardless,â€ he said. â€œI always try and get better. You canâ€™t stay stagnant in any sport. Youâ€™ve always got to keep getting better, because you know the guys are training harder; theyâ€™re refining their game.â€ Asked about their renewed rivalry, Mickelson said it was flattering. â€œTo me, anyway,â€ he quickly added. â€œProbably not to him, but itâ€™s flattering to me.â€ Mickelson began working with Harmon right before the Byron Nelson Championship at the end of April, and the results have been on the upswing. He was third at the Nelson, third at Wachovia and won The Players. With the U.S. Open approaching, former U.S. Open champion Johnny Miller gives Mickelson the edge. ALSO ON THIS STORY Discuss: Sound off on golf message boards â€œI believe heâ€™s the favorite right now,â€ Miller said Wednesday. â€œGive me Tiger or Phil right now, Iâ€™ll take Phil.â€ CONTINUED: 'Iâ€™m working hard,' Mickelson says Mickelson quits Memorial with wrist injury Tiger tested with baby, new tourney on way Expert: Don't expect Tiger to falter after fatherhood Fringe: Rift growing between PGA, Euro Tours Notebook: Bunker mentality returns to Muirfield Sound off on golf message boards Tracking Tiger: News, more on No. 1 golfer Interactive: Can Tiger catch Golde