http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-0&fd=R&url=http://www.buffalonews.com/cityregion/story/87856.html&cid=1116829994&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ The Buffalo News: City & Region The Buffalo News : City & Region Thursday, May 31, 2007 Click for Archives Only View Today's Front Page Buffalo / Erie County Adam Zyglis / Tom Toles Buffalo / Erie County Adam Zyglis / Tom Toles Gov. Eliot L. Spitzer supports the measure. Click to view a larger picture State to end price cap on brokered tickets - NEWS ALBANY BUREAU Updated: 05/31/07 7:26 AM ALBANY &#8212; A measure ending current price caps on how much scalpers and brokers can charge on tickets to sports and entertainment events is moving toward final approval by state lawmakers and Gov. Eliot L. Spitzer. A day after the measure was overwhelmingly approved by the Assembly, the governor Wednesday added his voice of support to bring a free-market system to the booming business of ticket reselling that has been bolstered in recent years by an assortment of Internet sites. The Senate is expected to approve the legislation today. The measure, depending on which side is believed in the debate, will either end up cutting or sharply raising the price of tickets to sports, theatrical and entertainment events that are resold by individuals, scalpers and ticket reselling outlets, such as StubHub. &#8220;Competition means lower prices,&#8221; said Sen. Dean Skelos, a Nassau County Republican and sponsor of the bill likely to be approved today in the Senate. After an intense lobbying campaign, which featured the likes of everyone from eBay to the Buffalo Bills and New York Yankees and some of Albany&#8217;s most influential lobbying firms, the legislative agreement ends a longtime price cap that now prohibits resellers from charging more than 45 percent above a ticket&#8217;s face value for events in venues with more than 6,000 seats. The Assembly on Tuesday passed the bill, 102-34. Critics say the measure will open the floodgates to price gouging by scalpers and ticket resale companies. But promoters insist a free market system will keep ticket prices from going sky high and could, depending on supply and demand pressures, cut resale prices. The governor said the regulation has been difficult to enforce, especially with a booming ticket resale business on the Internet. Further, he said the law &#8220;doesn&#8217;t make sense&#8221; to apply price controls on the so-called secondary ticket market when there is no cap placed by the state on a ticket&#8217;s first point of sale by arena and theater box offices. The governor did not if he would definitely sign the legislation, but he made clear his support, calling it &#8220;smart judgment&#8221; to let the current limits expire. In a floor debate in the Assembly Tuesday, detractors said the measure will have one effect: higher ticket prices, especially on moderate-income families who already find themselves being priced out of the regular ticket market. It will lift the cap that now applies to an array of ticket resellers, from eBay listings to TicketExchange, the Bills&#8217; ticket resell program. Assemblyman Sam Hoyt, DBuffalo, said officials with the Buffalo Bills earlier had urged him to vote against the measure; he said the Buffalo Sabres had remained neutral on the bill. Citing the difficulties of the Buffalo Bills to flourish in a smaller NFL market city, Hoyt said he did not want to back any effort that could hurt the team. &#8220;I&#8217;m very cautious about supporting any measure that may in face impact the economic strength of a particular industry, especially in this case the Buffalo Bills,&#8221; he told his colleagues Tuesday. Hoyt later acknowledged the Bills may have softened earlier opposition with the introduction of some amendments to the measure. Officials with the Bills and Sabres declined comment Wednesday. Lawmakers from downstate, meanwhile, lamented the effect on families being able to afford Broadway plays and other cultural events. &#8220;I think this bill is a real mistake. I think the wrongs that it will do are not what are in the minds of the [bill&#8217;s] sponsors, but the wrongs that it will do are very much in the minds of those pushing this bill,&#8221; said Assemblyman Richard Gottfried, D-Manhattan. Supporters say New York &#8212; in the face of ticket resales from brokers in states with no price caps and an increasing number of Internet ticket sales outlets &#8212; has been unable to enforce its own price cap law. &#8220;Market restrictions by statute, I believe, are no longer applicable in this day and age,&#8221; said Assemblyman Joseph Morelle, a Rochester Democrat who sponsored the measure in the Assembly. The online company eBay, in a memo backing the bill, said current law prevents New Yorkers from buying tickets beyond the price cap. &#8220;Many New Yorkers are therefore unable to purchase tickets to their favorite sporting events, concerns or other large entertainment venues while non-New Yorkers can purchase the tickets without any restrictions,&#8221; the company&#8217;s lobbying memo said. It said the measure replaces a system with &#8220;an arbitrary price cap&#8221; to ticket sales led by &#8220;traditional market forces.&#8221; Current law includes two caps: the 45 percent above face value for events in venues with more than 6,000 seats and a 25 cap above face value for tickets to events in venues with fewer than 6,000 seats. The legislation also: &#8226; Ends current local government licensure of ticket resale brokers, placing the role under the state Department of State. Those selling fewer than five tickets per event are not considered brokers and don&#8217;t have to register. &#8226; Prohibits restrictions being placed on fans by the operators of venues, such as professional sports teams, involving such things as the sale of season tickets to resale companies. The Yankees last year moved against a number of season ticket holders who tried to resell tickets on StubHub. &#8226; Keeps intact a 1,500-foot buffer zone around large arenas, and sets a new, 500-foot buffer for venues with fewer than 500 seats, inside which ticket scalping is illegal. New York state&#8217;s big sports teams &#8212; including the Bills, Sabres, Rangers, Yankees, Knicks and Mets &#8212; opposed the measure a month ago over concerns involving a season ticket holder provision. The teams were concerned the bill would limit their ability to cut off a season ticket holder who engaged in illegal or fraudulent acts when reselling tickets, such as selling one ticket to two different buyers. Legislative sources said the Yankees also were pressing to ensure that only they could be the resellers of tickets to Yankees games. The final version makes clear that the ticket holder &#8212; not the team &#8212; has the say over how a ticket can be resold. But it also included an amendment giving teams authority to discipline ticket holders who abuse ticket reselling. On Saturday, the pro teams added their support to the bill and the Assembly quickly pushed the measure to the floor. The current ticket scalping law is set to expire Friday. Breaking 24 Hour News Russia resists missile defense plan TB patient in Denver for treatment Putin: U.S. has triggered new arms race N.H. governor signs civil unions law More City & Region Stories 3 badly hurt in school bus-truck crash Two students face action in attacks on faculty at Sweet Home, Amherst State to end price cap on brokered tickets Rod Watson: Honor legacy of Tubman the right way Most Popular, Last 24 Hours Man found living in a bunker underground Jet boats rock the waterfront Several injured as Le Roy school bus hits dump truck Two students face action in attacks on faculty at Sweet Home, Amherst An offer of free televisions turns out to be arresting Esmonde: Sabres need to pay price of success Paladino, Ciminelli call for razing of AM&A's building A real beer fight Hyatt hotel to undergo $11 million renovation Canadian woman accused of importing 32 pounds of pot Man found living in a bunker underground 70 Wegmans in 4 days! Vitamin D may fight cancers Jet boats rock the waterfront Two students face action in attacks on faculty at Sweet Home, Amherst An offer of free televisions turns out to be arresting A real beer fight Hyatt hotel to undergo $11 million renovation Power Authority shift spurs WNY hopes State Broadcasters Hall of Fame taps local &#8216;institution&#8217; Neaverth Power Authority shift spurs WNY hopes Getting under the skin of drunk drivers Exhibits detail years of anti-smoking cartoons Russia says new ICBM can beat any system Schumer denounces rent-to-own industry Gitmo detainee apparently kills himself Vitamin D may fight cancers Two students face action in attacks on faculty at Sweet Home, Amherst M&T stays at the head of the SBA class Subscribe to the News Copyright 1999 - 2007 - The Buffalo News copyright-protected material. © 2007 The Buffalo News. The information you receive online from The Buffalo News is protected by the copyright laws of the United States. The copyright laws prohibit any copying, redistributing, re-transmitting, or re-purposing of any copyright-protected material.
http://www.sbsun.com/sports/ci_6025537&cid San Bernardino County Sun - Lowe leads Dodgers to 2nd shutout Lowe leads Dodgers to 2nd shutout Tony Jackson, Staff Writer Article Launched: 05/31/2007 12:14:58 AM PDT WASHINGTON - If this wasn't Derek Lowe at his finest, then pity the Washington Nationals if they ever do run into the vintage version. On a Wednesday night when he couldn't locate his breaking ball, Lowe managed seven shutout innings and 11 ground-ball outs in a 5-0 victory over the Nationals in front of 22,360 at RFK Stadium. With that, the Dodgers assured themselves of winning a series for the first and last time in the three-year lifespan of this ballpark, where they will make their final appearance tonight. In winning the first two games, the Dodgers have outscored the Nationals 15-0, marking the first time they have turned in consecutive shutouts in three years. "The final line score looked good, but it didn't tell the whole story," Lowe said. "I was (behind in counts) 3-1, 2-0, and you're not going to win many games like that. But you just have to trust your stuff and feel like it's going to come around." By the time the Dodgers staked him to a 2-0 lead in the fifth - the second run scoring on an RBI single by Rafael Furcal to run his hitting streak to a career best-tying 15 games - it had come around for Lowe, who retired 13 of his final 15 batters while allowing just one hit, an infield single by Guzman in the fifth that could have been ruled an error on rookie third baseman Tony Abreu. Sammy slams it home Bryant double-dribble aimed at Lakers NHRA sells drag racing series, track leases for $121 million Lowe leads Dodgers to 2nd shutout Angels knock out King Felix Sixers edge Quakes in low-scoring affair Schmidt, Anderson have mixed results Locals help RCC win state baseball title Diamond Bar loses out on title Bryant better be careful about what he wishes for Kunitz to get X-rays today For more local Southern California news: Los Angeles Daily News L