http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/9-4&fd=R&url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp%3Fymd%3D20070530%26content_id%3D1995621%26vkey%3Drecap%26fext%3D.jsp%26c_id%3Dmlb&cid=1116768078&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ The Official Site of Major League Baseball: News: Major League Baseball News MLB.TV: Live and On-Demand MLB.TV Mosaic Help Blog Player News and Notes Home Run Beat the Streak Staples Easy Fantasy Report Fantasy News and Notes Text Messaging – Alerts & More Manage Services – Mobile Dashboard MLB 2007 Mobile Game DHL Delivery of the Day 05/31/2007 1:26 AM ET Heart of Cards order snaps losing skid Pujols, Edmonds, Rolen drive in six of eight Redbirds runs By Matthew Leach / MLB.com Albert Pujols follows through on his three-run homer in the fifth inning. (Jack Dempsey/AP) &#149; Pujols' three-run homer &#149; Rolen goes 2-for-5 &#149; Taguchi's sliding catch &#149; Pujols, Edmonds go back-to-back Cards notes: Duncan, Spiezio still ailing Big inning downs Hirsh, win streak Rox notes: Win streak a total team effort Yanks snap slide with big win over Jays Tribe pound Dice-K in finale Weaver shaky but Angels rally D-backs sweep behind Johnson Zito dominant as Giants blank Mets A-Rod defends controversial shout Lowe, Dodgers blank Nationals Young brilliant; Greene powers Padres &#149; Pujols' three-run homer &#149; Taguchi's sliding catch &#149; Rolen goes 2-for-5 Cards notes: Duncan, Spiezio still ailing DENVER -- Dealing without catcher Yadier Molina will not be easy for the Cardinals. But it will be much more manageable if they have Scott Rolen and Jim Edmonds back. The two previously slumping sluggers continued their hot streaks on Wednesday night, joining with fellow "MV3" Albert Pujols to lead St. Louis to an 8-4 win over the Rockies at Coors Field. Pujols, Edmonds and Rolen combined for five extra-base hits and six RBIs, providing a much-needed boost to a lineup missing not only Molina but David Eckstein, Chris Duncan and Scott Spiezio. "Any time we play, when those three guys hit, we have a chance to score a lot of runs," said manager Tony La Russa. The offensive outburst provided Todd Wellemeyer with the support he needed to win in his first career Major League start. Wellemeyer lasted five-plus innings, allowing three runs on seven hits, striking out three and walking one. He looked shaky in the first two innings, but got through the next three without further damage. A leadoff homer in the sixth chased the right-hander. Rolen's RBI double in the first gave the Cardinals the lead, and Pujols scored on a wild pitch to make it 2-0. Colorado tied the game in the second, but Rolen doubled again in the fourth to score Edmonds, who had tripled. Edmonds picked up three-fourths of a cycle, missing only a double. Since May 14, Rolen is 17-for-47 (.362) with six doubles and a home run. He had six extra-base hits through the season's first six weeks. He has seven in the past two-plus weeks. "I haven't done much," he said. "I haven't lived up to my end of what I'm supposed to be doing. I understand that. I take responsibility. Right now I'm seeing the ball better, swinging better, and I'm being a little more selective. Hopefully I can continue that and everything will turn the corner for the whole team. I feel like I have a good base under me. I feel like my hands are working the way they should. And hopefully, I can stay consistent with that." For Wellemeyer, being handed a second lead was a boon. "That was huge," he said. "We went up 3-2, and I shut them down for three straight. Then we went up big time. So it was big." In the fifth, St. Louis broke the game open. A pair of singles set the table for Pujols, who drilled a three-run homer to center field. Edmonds followed with his fourth home run in his last six games. It was the first time all season that St. Louis hit back-to-back home runs. "We don't have but about 16 home runs between 10 of us, so I'm not surprised," quipped Edmonds. On the morning of May 8, Edmonds was batting .184 and slugging .253. Since then, he's 19-for-56 with six extra-base hits, for a .339 average and a .607 slugging percentage. "It's a long season," he said. I'm just trying to play catchup. Everybody's starting to put it together a little bit. We know that the three, four, five and probably six in this lineup have to produce for us to win." Wellemeyer finished the scoring in the big inning with a single that brought home Juan Encarnacion, who had doubled. That ended the night for Colorado starter Jason Hirsh, and made it pretty much a perfect night for Wellemeyer. "After today, I'm liking starting, getting some ABs," he said. "I love hitting." The Cards didn't score another run after the fifth, while Colorado threatened twice. After Jeff Baker's pinch-double in the seventh, So Taguchi made an impressive diving catch, then doubled Baker off to end the inning. Things got even scarier in the eighth. With two men on and the torrid Brad Hawpe at the plate, La Russa summoned Tyler Johnson -- who had permitted a homer to Hawpe one night earlier. Hawpe drilled a deep line drive that took Ryan Ludwick all the way to the wall, but Ludwick reined the ball in for the third out of the eighth. Jason Isringhausen turned in a 1-2-3 ninth. The win pulled the Cardinals back within 6 1/2 games of first-place Milwaukee in the National League Central. is a reporter for MLB.com. This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs. Register | Log In Help | Contact Us &copy; 2001-2007 MLB Advanced Media, L.P. All rights reserved. The following are trademarks or service marks of Major League Baseball entities and may be used only with permission of Major League Baseball Properties, Inc. or the relevant Major League Baseball entity: Major League, Major League Baseball, MLB, the silhouetted batter logo, World Series, National League, American League, Division Series, League Championship Series, All-Star Game, and the names, nicknames, logos, uniform designs, color combinations, and slogans designating the Major League Baseball clubs and entities, and their respective mascots, events and exhibitions. Use of the Website signifies your agreement to the Privacy Policy (updated 03.22.05)
http://www.mercurynews.com/sportsheadlines/ci_6026836&cid San Jose Mercury News - Stanley Cup: Anaheim in control san jose / valley start / stop paper (From the last 24 hours) ACLU targets planner of so-called CIA torture flights Prosecutors: Aptos woman lived high life on &#36;1.5 million stolen... Kawakami: Bryant reveals a tortured soul Spector defense targets forensic errors Rivals Steve Jobs, Bill Gates talk like old pals Stanley Cup: Anaheim in control LATE GOAL GIVES DUCKS 1-0 VICTORY, 2-0 SERIES LEAD Mercury News Wire Services Article Launched: 05/31/2007 01:44:22 AM PDT Click photo to enlarge Ottawa Senators goalie Ray Emery is scored on by Anaheim Ducks center Samuel Pahlsson, of Sweden, in the third period in Game 2 of the NHL Stanley Cup final hockey game Wednesday, May 30, 2007, in Anaheim, Calif. The Ducks won 1-0. (AP Photo/Mark J. Terrill) NHL notebook: Messier intrigued by N.Y. opening The Anaheim Ducks' defensive stalwarts are hurting the Ottawa Senators on offense, too. Samuel Pahlsson's shot beat Senators goalie Ray Emery with 5:44 left to give the Ducks a 1-0 victory over Ottawa on Wednesday and a 2-0 lead in the Stanley Cup finals. Pahlsson, a finalist to be the NHL's top defensive forward, joined linemate Travis Moen with winning goals in the series. They already mastered the job of shutting down Ottawa's high-flying top line and now are providing the finishing blows against the Eastern Conference champions. "We worked really hard the whole game for that one, but we couldn't get anything by Emery," Pahlsson said. "We just try to play our game, make it easy for us and hard for them. We got some goals and we don't expect that every game. It's fun." After a turnover by Dany Heatley, Pahlsson carried the puck down the right-wing boards, worked around Daniel Alfredsson, and let go a shot past defenseman Joe Corvo, who had his back to him. That matched Moen's winning tally that came with 2:51 left Monday. Saturday, the best-of-seven series will shift to Ottawa for the first time since 1927, and the Senators will have to figure out a way to break out of a scoring funk in the next two games to earn a trip back to Southern California. Teams that won the first two games at home have captured the Cup 29 of 30 times. Jean-Sebastien Giguere stopped 16 shots for his sixth postseason shutout and first this year. He leaped as time ran out and the loud duck call vibrated through a deafening arena. Emery made 30 saves for the Senators, who lost only once in each of their first three series. After a postseason low of 20 shots in the series opener, the Senators managed less of a punch in Game 2. But the game didn't lack exciting, tense play. Emery was brilliant and had the added bonus of a few quick whistles as he tried to freeze the puck. Senators Coach Bryan Murray complained after Game 1 that the Ducks delivered a few extra stick jabs after the whistle and the message was received by referees Bill McCreary and Brad Watson. The Mercury News is pleased to let readers post comments about an article at the end of the article. Please increase the credibility of your post by including your full name and city when commenting. Sorry, no items are currently available. Copyright 2007 San Jose Mercury News Privacy Policy and Terms of Use MNG Corporate Site Map
http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20070528.wsptduha28/BNStory/Sports/columnists&cid globeandmail.com: Duhatschek: Bettman points to game's improvements Letters to the Editor Duhatschek: Bettman points to game's improvements Globe and Mail Update May 28, 2007 at 8:08 PM EDT &#151; It wasn't a great time for the National Hockey League to take a week off last week, what with Rick Tocchet pleading guilty to running a sports-gambling ring; and the Nashville Predators getting sold to Canadian billionaire Jim Balsillie. Then there was everyone's favorite snub &#151; how NBC, its national over-the-air rights holder in the United States, cut away from the deciding game of the Eastern Conference final to show what amounted to a Preakness pre-race show. Most people probably would have understood if the network had cut away from its hockey coverage to televise a two-minute race they were contractually obliged to carry. The fact that it sacrificed the overtime of a conference championship game to spend an hour reflecting on what happened to Barbaro in last year's race was too much for hockey fans to bear, contract or no contract. Accordingly, it took a brave man to set foot in front of the assembled media hordes Monday and extol the virtue of the product that he was selling. That was commissioner Gary Bettman's duty Monday and true to form, he stayed mostly on message &#151; that while things were not perfect, the NHL's challenges were "a mere fraction of what they were a few years ago." The most revealing moments came when Bettman talked about Canada and the possible return of the NHL north of the 49th parallel. Bettman essentially said the possibility of a return to the two markets that the NHL left in the 1990s &#151; Winnipeg and Quebec &#151; "intrigues me" and that while it isn't something they've studied, "it seems to me more likely than it was two, three, four or five years ago." Years ago, Winnipeg and Quebec lost their teams, largely for building reasons. Winnipeg's new facility might just make the grade by the NHL's current arena standards, while the old Colisee in Quebec most definitely would not. And in the case of either market, a deep-pockets' ownership group would be needed to underwrite the cost of the franchise. In the post-lockout NHL, the going price for a team &#151; based on last week's developments &#151; is $220-million, the price Balsillie was willing to pay to snag the Predators. Bettman spoke in very formal terms whenever Balsillie's name came up and one wonders if he imagines that Balsillie might become his Mark Cuban, a maverick willing to use his wealth and power to rock what is still a fairly wobbly NHL boat. Balsillie isn't in the lodge yet and the last time he tried to buy a team &#151; the Pittsburgh Penguins &#151; the deal broke down before a formal transfer was approved. Given what the sale price has done to franchise value, it is hard to imagine Balsillie not getting the required three-quarters approval from the board when the matter comes to a vote on June 19. It'll be harder still for the board members to restrain themselves from giving Balsillie a standing ovation. When Bettman was asked about the possibility of Tocchet's reinstatement, he answered that no decision would be made until after the league completes its own internal investigation into the case and Tocchet is sentenced by a New Jersey court. If body language and tone mean anything, things didn't look too promising for Tocchet. Nor did Bettman think much of my suggestion that Toronto needed a second NHL team. "I live in New York and I can tell you, there are downsides to multiple teams in a market." On balance, Bettman was poised and in control of the proceedings in his unofficial, semi-annual state-of-the-union address. It isn't his job to slag the league for which he fronts; and in fact, he was a little less Pollyanna about some of its problems and prospects than he has been in the past, when all was right with the league &#151; even if it wasn't. On U.S. TV, Bettman said, "obviously it could be better." On the Preakness fiasco, he said: "You can second-guess it. I do myself." He put the blame for a season that spills into June squarely on ownership, saying that most teams wanted to start the season later rather than earlier. The only other possibility would be to reduce the length of the schedule and currently, there was no appetite for that either. And for anyone thinking the end of Bettman's reign is near, they can think again. Bettman turns 54 next week and acknowledged that his current contract runs until he turns 60. He said he likes what he's doing and as long as his employers feel the same way, he isn't planning on going anywhere anytime soon. It is 14 years now with Bettman at the helm and within the first few years of his reign, the NHL lost teams in both Winnipeg and Quebec. There would be something serendipitous about a return to those markets in the latter years of his career. Intriguing too. "Sometimes intrigue is a fanciful notion," said Bettman, "but if the right circumstances presented themselves and there was interest in a real meaningful way, then we would have to seriously look at it." Comments are closed for this story | Send a letter to the editor Add ERIC DUHATSCHEK to my e-mail alerts Thomas powers Athletics to series-opening win Chara named Bruins captain Saskin says Chelios lawsuit 'without merit' Devils get salary cap relief Go to the section Toil and trouble in China's growing stock bubble Former owner finds joy in team's success Senators-Ducks' Game 1 audience falls short Parkes making early departure Top Stories by Section CIBC profit rises sharply, but shares slip Governments, police share Ipperwash blame, probe says Canadian soldier among seven killed in Afghan helicopter crash Hewitt rallies to reach third round A robust hit that never falters Alleged top world spammer arrested in Seattle A 40-year wait for wedded bliss Tories take another swipe at 