http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-6&fd=R&url=http://vikings.scout.com/2/647918.html&cid=1116813826&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Scout.com: Competing League Coming (Then Going) Competing League Coming (Then Going) Posted May 31, 2007 The NFL faces another challenge from a rival football league. Unlike the most recent challenge -- the WWE-inspired XFL -- the United Football League is prepared to challenge the NFL at old-school football. But the bigger questions facing the new league are who will watch it and, more importantly, who will air it? The sports world was mildly abuzz Wednesday with the announcement that a rival league is forming to challenge the NFL. A league calling itself the United Football League includes such heavy hitters as one of the top dogs for Google Inc. and Dallas Mavericks renegade Mark Cuban as faceplates. The NFL declined comment on the matter, but thereâ€™s no reason for the NFL to be overly concerned about the potential new rival. Why? Where are they going to televise games? Both the NBA and NHL have shown why they arenâ€™t truly mainstream professional sports and each was on display last night. The NBA is at the conference championship level and if you want to see those games, you need to tune in cable channels like ESPN and TNT. Even worse is the NHL. Wednesday night was Game 2 of the Stanley Cup finals and the game was carried on the cable network Versus â€“ which is hard for many casual cable TV viewers to even locate. Even when the league has broadcast games on NBC, an overtime playoff game was pushed over to Versus between the third period and the overtime. Why? So NBC could do pre-race coverage of the Preakness Stakes. In Wednesdayâ€™s Game 2, the 1-0 win by Anaheim was seen on Versus, while NBC carried two hours of a show called â€œMost Outrageous Momentsâ€ â€“ a collection of raucous bloopers and injuries. The same fate is likely to be true for the new UFL. Unlike the last attempt to challenge the NFL â€“ the ill-fated XFL â€“ football is intended to be the primary source of entertainment, not wrestlers cutting promos and cheerleaders that look like no strangers to a stripper pole. They come in with good intentions and hope to achieve the success that the AFL had as being a legitimate rival and the lesser success that the USFL enjoyed by enticing some of the top college stars away. The reality is that even the XFL attempted to make a splash in the football market, and it had a national TV contract with NBC. The NFL has successfully eliminated that loophole by incorporating all four of the major television networks in its latest TV contract as well as working its own NFL Network into the mix. CBS carries the AFC contract, FOX has the NFC contract, NBC has weekly Sunday Night games and ESPN (owned along with ABC by the Disney Corporation) holds the Monday night contract. If any of the major networks were to start carrying the UFL, the NFL could easily flex its muscle and threaten to take off the NFL in its next bid package. Having the luxury of being able to bid on contracts with your own network should be a frightening concept to anyone â€“ much less someone trying to fight against the league. Most people in the initial reaction to the UFL (aside from laughing) are saying that the league will be viewed as inferior because of the power and lure of the NFL. The belief is that the only players that will come out as blue-chip college prospects will be the greedy types that are more about money than playing football. The rest of the league will consist of players who â€œcouldnâ€™t cut itâ€ in the NFL. But more important is that, with the current television contract status of the NFL, all four major networks are involved in deals with the NFL right now and that pursuing a deal with any new league would be akin to financial suicide. With the power the NFL wields at this time, itâ€™s unlikely any TV network would want to upset the league by helping a competitor. The NFL didnâ€™t feel obligated to comment on the announcement of the UFL plan to begin play next summer. Why should they? Without a network TV deal, the new league is doomed from the start, which precludes why the NFL should comment. Frazier Ready to Put His Stamp on Defense No June 1 Megacuts Coming Subscribe today and get a full year of with an annual Total Access Pass. Copyright &copy; VikingUpdate.com and . All rights reserved. This website is an unofficial and independent source of news and information, and is not affiliated with any school, team or league.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-5&fd=R&url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/golf/2007-05-30-woods-mickelson_N.htm&cid=1116756580&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ All eyes on Woods and Mickelson - USATODAY.com How do I find it? Buy and sell tickets to premium and sold out events Search by events or regions: Looking to sell tickets quick? All eyes on Woods and Mickelson By Jerry Potter, USA TODAY DUBLIN, Ohio &#8212; There could be no greater dream match for golf fans, the serious and the casual, than seeing going head-to-head at the Memorial Tournament, which begins Thursday at Muirfield Village. Just having the No. 1 and 2 players in the world at any event is interesting, but having them here on ' golf course in Jack's tournament ups the ante. Woods and Mickelson said Wednesday after the Memorial pro-am that they don't necessarily consider their situation a blood feud. But they have had some icy moments, notably when they were paired together in the opening round of the 2004 Ryder Cup. "It's flattering, at least to me anyway," Mickelson said when asked about the public's perception of a rivalry. "But it's probably not flattering to him." Woods' role is more like that of Nicklaus than Palmer because after Nicklaus established himself there was a succession of players, from to Lee Trevino to Johnny Miller to , who challenged for a while but not forever. "I've had different guys make different runs," Woods said. "It was David (Duval) then Phil and Ernie (Els), Vijay (Singh), Goose (Retief Goosen), a combination of those guys through out the years. As long as I'm a part of each of those conversations I'm doing all right." Mickelson, who turns 37 on June 16, says he'd need exceptional success to even catch Woods, who is 31. Mickelson has 31 wins on the PGA Tour, three of them majors, all coming since 2004. Woods has 57 Tour wins, including 12 majors. This year Mickelson won the AT&T Pebble Beach Pro-Am and The Players, which ranks next to a major in importance. Woods has three wins. He was second in The Masters and 37th in The Players. Mickelson was 24th in The Masters. Mickelson's victory in The Players, coupled with his switch to noted teacher Butch Harmon, who tutored Woods in some of his best years, has rekindled the thoughts of a renewed rivalry. "It's a tough feat," he said of challenging Woods. "We're talking about probably the best player of all time." Mickelson said he's not even thinking about overtaking Woods in the World Golf Ranking, adding, "It'll certainly be a while before anybody has a realistic chance at taking on Tiger because of the success that he has had." Woods has won the Memorial three times; Mickelson has never won it. "It's no different than any other tournament," Mickelson said. "He's probably won other tournaments more than three." Woods and Mickelson won't be alone &#8212; the 107-player Memorial field includes the top six players in the world and eight of the top 10 &#8212; but they will be certain to boost TV ratings, and a showdown between No. 1 and No. 2 would add to the interest. When asked Tuesday about Woods' dominance, Nicklaus said, "We don't know if anybody can get to that level. Right now, nobody is." To report corrections and clarifications, contact Reader Editor By Rob Carr, AP Phil Mickelson puts on his second green jacket after winning the Masters in 2006, with assistance from 2005 winner Tiger Woods. Both will be on hand for the Memorial Tournament this weekend. USA TODAY welcomes your thoughts, stories and information related to this article. Please stay on topic and be respectful of others. Keep the conversation appropriate for interested readers across the map. Newspaper Home Delivery - Subscribe Today Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Right Add USATODAY.com RSS feeds
