http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-2&fd=R&url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/sport/hewitt-finds-the-will-to-win/2007/05/31/1180205433136.html&cid=1116760279&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Hewitt finds the will to win - Sport - theage.com.au Welcome to The Age. Hewitt finds the will to win Australia's Lleyton Hewitt finds another backhand winner in his stunning comeback against Argentina's Gaston Gaudio. Lleyton Hewitt kept his French Open campaign alive last night with a stunning come-from-behind win over Argentina's Gaston Gaudio. Down two sets to love, the Australian pulled out one of his trademark fightbacks to defeat the 2004 French champion 4-6, 3-6, 6-2, 6-4, 6-2 on centre court. The Australian is now on track to meet claycourt master Rafael Nadal in the fourth round if he can overcome Finland's Jakko Nieminen, seeded 20, who had an easy 6-1, 6-1, 6-4 win against Frenchman Mathieu Montcourt. Hewitt wore down Gaudio over three hours 28 minutes, finding his range in the third set after a slow start. His best result for the French Open was making the quarter-finals in 2001 and 2004. Last year, he made it through to the fourth round. It's been a good start to the French Open for Australians, with Samantha Stosur's liking for a challenge and cool head under pressure securing her a place in the French Open third round for the first time, uncharted territory in which she will encounter Czech No. 6 seed Nicole Vaidisova. Stosur was struggling in the third set of her second-round match against Maria Kirilenko, but came back from a rain delay to immediately convert a crucial break point and calmly complete a 6-1, 3-6, 7-5 victory over the Russian. "This tournament's always been hard for me and I'm just really, really happy to be in the third round for the first time," said Stosur, who is due to meet Vaidisova tonight (Melbourne time). "Hopefully, it won't stop here." Stosur, the No. 27 seed, went into the match having equalled her best performance at Roland Garros by making the second round, which she also achieved in 2005. But she was determined to go at least one better. "It was a very tight match and at the end, I think I got a little bit tired," the Australian said. "I knew she was kind of feeling the same thing, so it was just a matter of being out there and really moving my feet, really just enjoying the challenge. "In the end, I came up with the right shots at the right time and won." Vaidisova has played Stosur three times, all last year, and the 18-year-old world No. 10 from Prague has won every time. But the 30th-ranked Stosur has recent form on clay, having beaten then-top seed Amelie Mauresmo in the second round of the Italian Open last month. And now that she has started to enjoy playing on clay, she doesn't want to stop. "I've played Nicole a handful of times, never actually beaten her, so it will be fun to go out there and play her again," Stosur said. "Third round, I'll just go out there and enjoy it and play the way I play." The first round of these rain-hit championships was finally completed yesterday, producing an unwanted record for American men, none of whom progressed to the second round of a grand slam tournament for the first time since the Open era began in 1968. Robby Ginepri was the last of the nine to bow out, losing from two sets to one up against Argentina's Diego Hartfield. World No. 1 Roger Federer was none too pleased with proceedings, either, slamming officials for scheduling his second-round match to start and finish in murky conditions. Federer, who needs a Roland Garros title to complete the full set of majors, finished his 6-1, 6-2, 7-6 (10-8) win over French wildcard Thierry Ascione just before 9.15pm (Paris time), with Court Suzanne Lenglen almost in darkness. "When we shook hands, I told him I couldn't see him any more, it was so dark," Federer said. "The conditions were shocking. I know they want to get the matches over and done with but what I don't like is that they know I'm the favourite and they think I should win in straight sets. 'Let's get Roger's match over and done with, then he's happy, he has a day off.' But what if it doesn't turn out this way? I would be very upset. I already wasn't happy playing so late." Nor were the locals pleased, with hopes of a first French Open men's singles title since Yannick Noah nearly a quarter-of-a-century ago in tatters. French veterans Sebastien Grosjean, Arnaud Clement and Fabrice Santoro all failed to make it past the first round, to the dismay of the partisan Parisian crowds. And matters got distinctly worse when French No. 1 Richard Gasquet had a nightmare against Belgium's Kristof Vliegen, booed off centre court after losing 7-6 (7-4), 6-3, 6-1. Gael Monfils and doubles expert Michael Llodra gave the crowds something to cheer, while Mauresmo, who is short of practice having missed two months after an appendix operation, defeated American Laura Granville 6-0, 7-5. Second seed Maria Sharapova saw off the challenge of another Frenchwoman, Emilie Loit, 6-3, 7-6 (7-4) in one hour 50 minutes. When you see news happening: SMS/MMS: 0406 THE AGE (0406 843 243), or us. Subscribe to The Age for your chance to win 12 years of Penfolds Grange! Hewitt finds the will to win Australia's Lleyton Hewitt finds another backhand winner in his stunning comeback against Argentina's Gaston Gaudio. Place a classified ad Copyright &#169; 2007. The Age Company Ltd. Browse for a Date Simoni wins mountain stage, Di Luca keeps lead No way, Jose &#151; didgeridoo man had wrong Telstra New series on track, says chief 'Betrayed' mum pays out on Lion Notting Ducks take early lead over Senators in final Swifts unlikely to repeat French connection We're to blame for rule change &#151; ex-ump Russo All-rounder Ron Archer a precocious talent all round Eye for an eye &#151; $9344 plunge now in limbo California doesn't give flying Ducks too much thought Flying Phoenix demolishes weary Swifts Loren lands in Oz Fans greet movie legend with flowers as she arrives for a film festival. Britney's ex to fund own second album and star opposite Keanu Reeves. Who gave Lohan alcohol? Officials ponder whether Lindsay Lohan, who is underage, was served alcohol in LA bars. Lock up the crackberry? Unique (and extreme) ways to get away from work for the hols. ALL MEN ARE LIARS Is this the only way to give up smoking? Weapons of seduction - II SAM AND THE CITY TV How far would you go to get laid? Sleepless world record attempt amusingly goes wrong. TODAY'S TOP 10 ARTICLES Big-spending mayor goes for broke TV news boss to spend weekends in jail Beware the psycho boss, the new enemy within Icy blast heralds winter Dr Karl's IR prescription? Man bites, and chews, dog in royal revenge Snow joy as resorts equip for hard time Only way is up, baby Fury over Timor inquest More most viewed articles News Store Alert will keep you informed. Get free news emails from theage.com.au.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/12i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.spokesmanreview.com/ap/story.asp%3FAP_ID%3DD8PF6RMG0&cid=1116777936&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ SR.com: Guerrero's 3-Run Homer Lifts Angels 8-6 Submit a news tip Home & Garden &raquo; Guerrero's 3-Run Homer Lifts Angels 8-6 Los Angeles Angels' Vladimir Guerrero watches the flight of his three-run home run in the fifth inning of an MLB baseball game against the Seattle Mariners in Anaheim, Calif., Wednesday, May 30, 2007. (AP Photo/Chris Pizzello) ANAHEIM, Calif. &mdash; It isn't often the Los Angeles Angels get home runs from their 3-4-5 hitters in the same game. They came at the right time, because Jered Weaver didn't have his best stuff. Vladimir Guerrero hit a go-ahead, three-run shot off Felix Hernandez, Gary Matthews Jr. and Casey Kotchman hit consecutive home runs in the first, and the Angels bullpen preserved an 8-6 win over the Seattle Mariners on Wednesday night. "It's good, because there are going to be sometimes when we're not going to do well offensively and our pitchers pick us up and keep us in close ballgames," Guerrero said through a translator. "We have a good pitching staff, and hopefully all of us can contribute to them." Guerrero's homer was his first since May 17 at Seattle. It hasn't been easy getting good pitches to hit, because everyone is pitching around the 2004 AL MVP. Guerrero's greatest strength is he is one of the game's best bad-ball hitters. "I can't get frustrated because it's part of the game. I've been saying that for a long time," Guerrero said. "I don't get frustrated because I trust the people that hit behind me. The home runs just happen when they happen. I don't worry about when they come or when they don't come. But I'm very happy that this one came tonight." Dustin Moseley (4-0) got the win in relief of Weaver, who was pulled after 4 2-3 innings with the Angels down 5-4. After Guerrero's homer put Los Angeles ahead 7-5, Moseley pitched two innings and gave up an RBI double to Raul Ibanez that cut the Angels' edge to 7-6 in the sixth. But Scot Shields pitched a perfect eighth and Francisco Rodriguez worked the ninth for his 18th save in 19 chances. Hernandez (3-3) allowed seven runs and nine hits in seven innings. He surrendered his first three homers of the season, as the Angels took the rubber game of the series and extended their lead in the AL West to 5 1/2 games over the second-place Mariners. "We were a little disappointed because we felt we had a chance to win the game with our ace on the mound," Adrian Beltre said. "It didn't happen, but we're going to get a chance to face these guys again, and hopefully we can do better next time. We've got four months left, so one series is not going to make a difference right now." Seattle's Ichiro Suzuki extended his hitting streak to 23 games _ tying his career best in 2001. The two-time AL batting champion is within one game of the franchise record set by Joey Cora in 1997. Weaver had won his previous three starts, and the Angels gave him a 4-1 lead in the first inning. But the Mariners made it 4-all on Beltre's RBI double in the fifth and Yuniesky Betancourt followed with an RBI single that finished the right-hander. "My command just really wasn't there," Weaver said. "The off-speed stuff felt great, but I was struggling with my fastball command. I just couldn't make my pitches and they put some good swings on the ball." Pinch-hitter Robb Quinlan drove in an insurance run in the Angels seventh with a sacrifice fly that Betancourt caught. The shortstop made an over-the-shoulder catch in short left-center field and couldn't get the ball home fast enough after Reggie Willits tagged up. Guerrero had a chance to break open the game in the eighth, but struck out with the bases loaded against Brandon Morrow. The rookie reliever extended his scoreless streak to 15 2-3 consecutive innings. The Mariners wrapped up a 6-4 road trip that began with a makeup game in Cleveland and continued through Tampa Bay, Kansas City and Anaheim. When they return to Seattle, the journey will have covered 6,273 miles. "It's going to be good to get back home," Beltre said. "We finished the road trip over .500 and we could have done better, but it was a good trip." Notes:@ Angels infielder Erick Aybar started at third base for the first time in his professional career. Normally a second baseman, he made a neat play on the first batter of the game, making a diving stop on Suzuki's grounder in the hole and throwing him out from one knee. ... Angels RHP Bartolo Colon's next scheduled start on Sunday was pushed back to June 8, when the club opens a nine-game road trip at St. Louis. The 2005 AL Cy Young winner, experiencing tightness in his triceps since early this month, has allowed 15 runs in 10 2-3 innings over his last two starts. Enter your search terms River Park Square independent analysis Details and conversations on the Washington News Council's analysis of River Park Square coverage &raquo; a journal of their experiences &raquo; All Cougs, All the Time WSU schedule, stories, photos Latest news from AP Economy Has Worst Growth Since 2002 TB Patient in Denver for Treatment N.H. Governor Signs Civil Unions Law Iraq Suicide Blast Leaves Up to 25 Dead Putin: U.S. Has Triggered New Arms Race Government Awards $20B Telecom Contract Man Described As a Top Spammer Arrested Last updated at 8:53 a.m. The Spokesman-Review is in its 125th year of publishing. Take with photos, historic pages and more. Ocularist Kim Erickson creates custom artificial eyes for people who have lost an eye to disease or injury. Officer Lee Newbill Memorial The Legacy of the Olmsted Brothers Time on His Hands Colin's Video Journal &raquo; Subscribe to video in iTunes &raquo; More live shows &raquo; Star Wars postage stamps Readers report local prices of our six-month series of editorial board conversations with community leaders. Streaming video of our weekday 10 a.m. news meeting: Catch up on 