http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-3&fd=R&url=http://www.pga.com/news/grantmethis/GMT_052907.cfm&cid=1116756580&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Grant Me This: What a Tiger Tour might mean for the world of golf It hasn't worked in other sports, but golf could be the exception. Columnist Grant Boone explores the idea that Tiger Woods could create his own golf circuit, and what that would mean to the PGA TOUR and to golf fans everywhere. A Tiger Woods golf circuit could generate great ratings and still allow Woods his chase of history. (Getty Images) Stanford leads Coastal Carolina as the men&#39;s NCAA finals get under way Ferguson on Golf: Jack and Tiger are at home on the range at Muirfield Memorial Notebook: Case of beer gets the best of Parnevik&#39;s toe After two months off, Sorenstam is ready to play again at the Ginn Tribute A year after barely missing a 59, Archer returns to the Wales Open Grant Boone, special to PGA.com 05.30.2007 08:48 pm (ET) First off, I&#39;m going to risk being trite to extend admittedly generic but heartfelt Memorial Day thanks to anyone and everyone who&#39;s put himself or herself in harm&#39;s way on behalf of this nation. I have conflicting thoughts when I think of conflicts. I&#39;m anti-war but pro-soldier. I&#39;m pro-U.S. but not anti-everyone else. I could probably be persuaded into believing there have been times and places in which war was either justified or inevitable. I get the idea that there are truly evil people on the planet who, unchecked, will wreak havoc on innocent lives. Generally speaking, though, I think war is usually waged by individuals or groups with something significant to gain. As for what&#39;s presently going on in Iraq, I think we can all agree -- however much you like (me, on some days) or dislike (me, on others) George W. Bush -- that we haven&#39;t seen an exit strategy this poorly conceived or executed since Jean V.D. Velde at the 1999 British Open. Still, that doesn&#39;t negate the sacrifices made by the U.S. military. And the idea that someone would risk his or her life to allow me the freedom to sit here and take the occasional potshot at The First Consonant is mind-boggling. There is scarcely a greater notion concocted by humankind than that of a person laying down his or her life for another. To all of you who&#39;ve served in America&#39;s armed forces, I thank you. Second, I couldn&#39;t help but think of professional golf as I watched the Indianapolis 500, what there was of it, for a couple of reasons. One, reducing what&#39;s supposed to be the crown jewel of your sport to by 34 laps is tantamount to abdicating your throne. Imagine the USGA shortening the U.S. Open to a 54-hole event. You&#39;d sooner see David Fay in a necktie. Officials at the Indy 500, on the other hand, called the race early but still bequeathed their wreath and jug to the putative winner, Dario Franchitti. They should&#39;ve given him skim milk. It&#39;s yet another example of how one of America&#39;s great sporting events is stuck in the pits. While the weather struck a blow against the race this year, the damage sustained 11 years ago was purely self-inflicted and is the other reason I thought about golf as I watched the fits and starts in Indy. The Indianapolis 500 was once the pace car of what was then the CART series, far and away the most important of the 15 or so annual races. The field each year was filled with the best drivers of that league. CART racing at the time was a fringe sport, for sure, but its stars were utterly mainstream and their names still resonate: Foyt, Andretti, Unser. In 1996, Tony George, owner of Indianapolis Motor Speedway, brought out a monkey wrench. He not only created a rival circuit, the Indy Racing League, he went one worse and reserved most of the spots on the Indy 500 grid for drivers in his new alliance. It splintered the sport and watered down one of America&#39;s great sporting events. Case in point: the winner of the first 500 after the split was Buddy Lazier. Not exactly a name to go alongside the aforementioned appellations in the pantheon of racing heroes. It&#39;s pronounced "luh ZEER," though it&#39;s true the general sports fan has been lazier in following open wheel racing in the U.S. ever since. I thought about all of this in relation to my own conjecture of a Tiger Tour. I&#39;ve wondered, along with others, what would happen if Tiger Woods -- fully aware of the staggering disparity in television ratings between events he plays and those he doesn&#39;t -- decided to renounce his PGA Tour membership and create his own series of tournaments. He could stage whatever number he preferred -- maybe 10 to 12 -- with small, elite fields and find his own tournament sponsors and broadcast partners. CBS, NBC, and Golf Channel are already shelling out a billion dollars for PGA Tour rights even though they know Woods won&#39;t play in two-thirds of the tournaments each season. The 12-14 he does play make it worth it to them. How much would ESPN/ABC pony up for a dozen Tiger Tour events with a guarantee of Woods&#39; presence in each? Here&#39;s where this idea is disturbingly different from what happened with CART and the Indy Racing League: Tiger would still compete in each of the four major championships because none of them are run by the PGA Tour. If, for example, Augusta National decided to start its own tour and insist that golfers play those events to earn a spot in the Masters, that tournament would eventually become irrelevant if the field didn&#39;t include Woods and the other best players of the day. That&#39;s essentially what Tony George did when he made the Indy 500 a closed shop. But Tiger could have the best of both worlds: his own tour and the opportunity to continue his pursuit of the one record he cares about most, Nicklaus&#39; 18 majors. Remember, Woods can play the Masters, British Open, and PGA Championship every year as a past champion. The U.S. Open gives its winners a 10-year exemption, meaning Woods is in that field through at least 2012. That would give him six more years to win another Open and extend his free pass. Even if he didn&#39;t win another one by then, I have a hunch he could snag one of those USGA special exemptions. In creating a rival league, Woods would obviously surrender his PGA Tour membership. And even if the Tour blackballed him from The Players or World Golf Championships by rearranging the eligibility criteria, he&#39;d still have a full season playing his own tour, the four majors, and whatever Tour events he wanted on sponsors&#39; invitations. (My guess is that Woods could finagle an exemption or two from Buick.) There would be significant obstacles, not the least of which might be Tiger even considering the possibility and his chief rivals, et al, being willing to leave the PGA Tour, too. The irony, though, is that the outcome -- at least in the short run -- could actually have the opposite effect of what happened with CART and the IRL. You&#39;re telling me golf fans wouldn&#39;t watch Tiger, Phil, Ernie, Vijay, Boo (just seeing if you&#39;re still with me), and 50 other solid players duke it out for $5 million purses on classic courses like Pinehurst, Pebble, and Winged Foot? (They might have a tough time booking the TPC Sawgrass, but I bet they could get a deal on the courses currently being concocted by the good folks at Tiger Woods Design.) Of course we&#39;d watch. And we&#39;d still get Tiger and all of those players going at it in the tournaments that matter most to us and them, the majors. I&#39;m not suggesting any of this is going to happen. What I am saying is that it could happen, which is why PGA Tour commissioner Tim Finchem walks such a fine line. He needs to come off as his own man while at the same time making sure Woods is happy. Which might explain the FedEx Cup. For all the talk about the $10 million first prize, the most notable characteristic is the shortened season, which Woods has wanted for years. That fine line might also explain why the Tour stiffed its rank-and-file by making sure the new event in Washington, D.C., which is being hosted by Tiger and which benefits Woods&#39; eponymous foundation, has the limited field Tiger wanted. It will be interesting to see if that event, titled the AT&T National, proves to placate Woods or give him a taste of what the Tiger Tour might one day be. All of this must surely raise a flag at PGA Tour headquarters, if not red then at least a yellow for caution. Because in golf right now, just as it was for American open wheel racing a decade ago, it would appear that one man is in the driver&#39;s seat. Grant Boone is a husband, father, golf broadcaster, and sports journalist based in Abilene, Texas. His column appears on PGA.com each Wednesday and every day during major championships and other big events. He can be contacted at The views and opinions expressed here do not reflect those of PGA.com or The PGA of America. PGA Grand Slam of Golf 2006 Sr. PGA Champ. 2007 Sr. PGA Champ. PGA Prof. Nat'l Champ. 2006 Sr. PGA Nat. Champ Srixon PGA Tourn. Series Callaway West. Wint. Champs. Teach. & Coach. Summit PGA Player of the Year Receive PGA.com Features, Offers and Alerts e-mails. Thank you for submitting your email. You will receive offers as they become available. &copy; 2003-2007 PGA/Turner Sports Interactive. All Rights Reserved. Send all feedback / comments to . Sales inquiries contact
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-5&fd=R&url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/03/sports/playmagazine/0603play-business.html%3Fref%3Dsports&cid=1116813826&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ First and Long &#151; Very Long - New York Times First and Long — Very Long Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: June 3, 2007 Bill Hambrecht is a rich old Wall Street guy who has made his money tilting at windmills and disrupting the establishment. “That’s what I do,” he says. “It’s fun.” Almost a decade ago, at 62, he founded WR Hambrecht + Company, whose fundamental premise is that companies don’t need to use Wall Street investment bankers — and pay their outrageous fees — to go public. Hambrecht + Company has since become so threatening to traditional underwriters that they often refuse to be involved in any I.P.O. in which his firm takes part. Skip to next paragraph Illustration by David Johnson The New York Times Go to Complete Coverage » And now, at an age when most people are well into retirement, he has decided to tackle the establishment again. This time, though, the establishment isn’t Wall Street. It’s the National Football League. Bill Hambrecht, you see, is starting up a professional football league. So far, he and his partner, Tim Armstrong, a senior executive at Google, have pledged $2 million each. They’ve hired a C.E.O. and a C.O.O., both of whom cut their teeth at the National Basketball Association. They’ve got a name: the United Football League. And they’ve lined up a wealthy, well-known businessman as their first owner: , the billionaire who owns the N.B.A.’s . Like Hambrecht, Cuban loves nothing more than confronting the status quo. Obviously, the U.F.L. is still in the early planning stages. It hasn’t yet hired a single football person and is still hunting for seven more owners with Cuban’s deep pockets and contrarian mindset, so that the league can begin with eight teams. It could easily fall apart before the first kickoff. Indeed, there has already been one setback: Boone Pickens, the oilman turned-corporate-raider-turned-billionaire-hedge-fund manager, recently abandoned his intention to buy a team. But Cuban remains committed, and if all goes according to plan, the U.F.L. will play its first preseason games in August 2008. I kid you not. Hambrecht has been thinking unconventional thoughts about pro football for a long time. Back in the early 1980s, he was a minority partner in the Oakland Invaders, one of the original franchises of the late, unlamented United States Football League, a spring league that played its games during the N.F.L.’s off-season. The U.S.F.L. folded in 1985, after three seasons. “It was started by a bunch of guys who were riding high because of the S.&L. boom,” Hambrecht recalls. “As soon as the boom turned to bust, the league went broke.” Most of us would go through such an experience and conclude, Never again. Not Hambrecht. He was convinced that the U.S.F.L. could have worked with a smarter game plan and owners who were more patient. At various times he discussed a new league with NBC, CBS and Fox, but those talks went nowhere. Then one day last year, Hambrecht told Tim Armstrong, whom he met when his firm helped manage Google’s initial public offering, about his dream of a new football league. The more Armstrong heard, the more excited he got. By October, the two men had committed their $2 million, hired their first three executives (Bill Daugherty, the C.E.O.; Jon Brod, the C.O.O.; and Andrew Goldberg, a senior analyst) and begun an extensive study to see if the idea was really feasible. Let’s now take a moment to consider what the U.F.L. will be up against: a monopolistic sports league utterly unafraid to take advantage of its monopoly power. Over the years, the N.F.L. has squashed four competitors, most recently the NBC- and World Wrestling Federation-backed XFL in 2001. Right now, Arena Football is an alternate league, but it’s a marginal thing, with negligible TV ratings and an average of 12,000 fans per game. And with eight players to a side, games in the N.F.L.’s off-season and a field that looks like a hockey rink, it’s not exactly “real” football. Where others might be daunted by the N.F.L.’s success and power, though, Hambrecht came to believe its monopoly status gave him an opening. “I really started thinking hard about this after the Los Angeles Rams left to go to St. Louis and the Houston Oilers went to Nashville,” he told me over drinks recently. “Why do you leave two of the top 10 TV markets in the country for these two smaller markets?” The answer, of course, is that the N.F.L. doesn’t really have to worry about where its teams are located, since most games are televised and the bulk of the league’s revenues come from its network contracts. What’s more, with the right stadium deal and enough corporate sponsorship, team owners can make as much (or more) money in smaller cities as they can in larger ones. That’s why the N.F.L. does just fine despite not fielding a team in 21 of the country’s top 50 markets — including such enormous metropolitan areas as San Antonio, Las Vegas, Orlando and (of course) Los Angeles. Nor does the N.F.L., which now has 32 teams, have much incentive to expand. On the contrary: expansion dilutes the TV money. (Greg Aiello, the N.F.L.’s spokesman, told me that “expansion isn’t on the table right now.”) Joe Nocera is a business columnist for The New York Times. Next Article in Sports (7 of 26) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. PRO FOOTBALL; Still Invitation Only, but Jets Widen Door for Camp PRO FOOTBALL; Giants Both Hopeful and Wary of One Rookie's Potential PRO FOOTBALL; Citing Lighter Penalties, Titan Is Appealing Ban PRO FOOTBALL; The Jets Trade Up and Home In for Defensive Help Next Article 