d. "We're going to look at it with the competition committee. We're going to look at it with the [general] managers and ultimately with the Board [of Governors]," Bettman said. "The first judgment that will have to be made is, is that a significant issue and is that something we need to address?" he said. "Even-strength goals are actually up. There are less penalties, not because we're relaxing the standard, but because everybody's adjusting to it. So the number of power-play goals is where the falloff was in scoring," Bettman said. Bettman also said that the league might look more favorably upon a bid to move a team to Canada by Jim Balsillie, who has signed a letter of intent to buy the Nashville Predators after a bid to buy the Pittsburgh Penguins was rejected. Bettman stressed that no move is in the planning stages and Balsillie has told him that there are no plans to shift the team to Canada, as he had hinted might happen with the Penguins. But Bettman also said he is intrigued by the idea of having another team in hockey-mad Canada. "That's something that, while we haven't studied it, seems to be more likely than it was three, four, five years ago," Bettman said. "If the right circumstances presented themselves and there was an interest in a real meaningful, material way, it's something we would have to obviously look at seriously. But beyond that, we haven't gone to the next step," he said. Bettman did note that the Predators, who have struggled to draw fans despite a strong season on the ice, have a 14-year lease but said that an escape clause could see the team free to leave much sooner. Bettman also addressed the controversy around former Phoenix Coyotes associate coach Rick Tocchet, who on Friday pleaded guilty to charges of conspiracy to promote gambling and promoting gambling. "Rick Tocchet pled guilty to a Grade 3 felony. He has yet to be sentenced," Bettman said. "I'm not really in a position to say what's going to happen until there's a complete disposition of his case. This story has been viewed 305 times. Copyright &copy; 1999-2007 The Taipei Times. All rights reserved.
http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/LAC.20070531.SENSNAT31/TPStory/Sports&cid globeandmail.com: Pahlsson steals the spotlight Letters to the Editor 2007 STANLEY CUP: NHL: GAME 2: DUCKS 1, SENATORS 0 Pahlsson steals the spotlight Anaheim's top checker scores game's lone goal, gives Ducks 2-0 series lead -- This has turned into a Sami Pahlsson-type of spring. The Anaheim Ducks' centre, who has found the National Hockey League playoff spotlight because of his stingy work on the defensive side of the puck, continued to lift his team with some timely offence. Pahlsson, who scored the series-winner against the Detroit Red Wings to put the Ducks into the Stanley Cup final, scored only his third goal of the playoffs on a screen shot with 5 minutes 44 seconds remaining to give the Ducks a 1-0 victory over the Ottawa Senators last night and a 2-0 lead in the series, which will shift to Ottawa for the next two games at Scotiabank Place on Saturday and Monday. The game-winning play, which transpired before a sellout crowd of 17,258 at the Honda Center, began when Senators forward Dany Heatley turned the puck over at the Anaheim blueline. Print Edition - Section Front Instead of dumping the puck in, Heatley attempted a cute pass to linemate Jason Spezza and the puck squirted to Pahlsson. Senators captain Daniel Alfredsson was unable to stymie his Swedish countryman on the backcheck and Pahlsson's shot beat Senators goaltender Ray Emery, who was screened by Ottawa defenceman Joe Corvo. &#34;On that particular play, we turned the puck over and Alfredsson couldn't get his stick on him,&#34; Senators head coach Bryan Murray said. &#34;That's been the key. We're committing turnovers and creating chances for them.&#34; The Ducks' checking line also scored the game-winner in the first game of the series, when Travis Moen put the puck into the net late in the third period on Monday. &#34;[Anaheim's] defence and checking line have been the stars so far,&#34; Murray said. In the territorial play, the Ducks completely dominated the second game. They outshot the Senators 30-16 (60-36 in the series so far), missed 18 more, while the Senators blocked 20 more. Ottawa, on the other hand, has had difficulty generating any sustained periods of offensive pressure. &#34;They keep the puck on the outside very well,&#34; Murray said. &#34;We had some good fore-checks, but couldn't take advantage of it. &#34;We have to take advantage of our home ice.&#34; Senators forward Peter Schaefer had a half-open net to shoot at with slightly more than three minutes remaining, but his rebound attempt was deflected wide off the stick of Anaheim defenceman Sean O'Donnell. Ducks goalie Jean-S&#233;bastien Gigu&#232;re earned his sixth career playoff shutout as he blanked the Senators, who have not scored in the past 90:24 of the series. The Senators showed up for the the second game with new line combinations, as Murray decided to split up his No. 1 trio of Spezza, Alfredsson and Heatley, although they were together on power plays. Spezza and Heatley played alongside tough guy Chris Neil, while Alfredsson played with centre Mike Fisher and Schaefer. The Senators' third line featured Chris Kelly between Antoine Vermette and Mike Comrie. Murray replaced fourth-liner Patrick Eaves in the lineup with Oleg Saprykin, who scored a game-winning goal early in the Eastern Conference final against the Buffalo Sabres. So how did the Ducks counteract the Senators' alterations? Head coach Randy Carlyle kept his checking specialists - Pahlsson, Rob Niedermayer and Travis Moen, the hero of the first game - against Spezza. The Ducks' No. 1 unit of Andy McDonald, Teemu Selanne and Andrew Miller went up against the Alfredsson line. Both teams had three power-play opportunities in the goalless opening 20 minutes. The Senators had a 68-second 5-on-3 advantage, during which Comrie slammed a rebound attempt off the post. The Ducks had two close calls early in the period, but Emery stopped shots by Selanne and Ryan Getzlaf. The Pahlsson line got the better of its opponents early in the second period, but either failed to finish or could not find a way to beat Emery. Spezza was reunited with Alfredsson and Heatley later in the second period, a move recommended by former Detroit Red Wings head coach Scotty Bowman when he discussed strategy with Murray earlier in the week. Bowman counselled Murray to break up his big line, only to reunite it periodically. Number of 5-on-5 goals for the Ottawa Senators during the first and second games of the Stanley Cup final. Sami Pahlsson of the Anaheim Ducks skates by Ottawa's Daniel Alfredsson to score the game-winner with less than six minutes to play in the third period. For the second game in a row, Ottawa fails to score on a 5-on-3 advantage. Top Stories by Section CIBC profit rises sharply, but shares slip Governments, police share Ipperwash blame, probe says Canadian soldier among seven killed in Afghan helicopter crash Hewitt rallies to reach third round A robust hit that never falters Alleged top world spammer arrested in Seattle A 40-year wait for wedded bliss Tories take another swipe at Dion Canadian soldier among seven killed in Afghan helicopter crash Senators slide into 2-0 hole Has big business turned organics into 'yuppy chow'? &#169; Copyright 2007 CTVglobemedia Publishing Inc. All Rights Reserved. The Globe and Mail are divisions of CTVglobemedia Publishing Inc., Submit post to digg.com Seed this post at Newsvine Technorati links to this post
