ngs. He struck out Moeller and Belisle to end the fifth and was finished after 79 pitches. Rick White relieved to start the sixth and gave up a double to Hopper and a single to Hatteberg. Left-hander Trever Miller came on and walked Ken Griffey Jr. to load the bases. Lidge, who hadn't pitched since bruising his knee in San Francisco on May 21, replaced Miller and struck out Phillips. Dunn then flew out to deep center to score Hopper and tie it at 1. Belisle retired 11 consecutive Astros, four on strikeouts, after Morgan Ensberg's two-out single in the third. Lee ended the streak in the seventh with a one-out single to left, but Hunter Pence grounded into an inning-ending double play. With one out in the eighth, Hatteberg hammered Qualls' 2-0 pitch into the Astros' bullpen in right center. It was Hatteberg's fifth homer of the season and his second in three days. He hit career homer No. 100 against Pittsburgh on Saturday. Belisle got the first two outs of the eighth and was relieved by left-hander Jon Coutlangus, who struck out Jason Lane. Notes: Hopper led off and started in center field, both effects of his collision with Ryan Freel on Monday. The Reds placed Freel on the 15-day disabled list before the game. "Ads published on this site are not for republication in print or web media without the expressed written consent of both the advertiser and The Brown Publishing Company." , All Rights Reserved
