http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/31/sports/baseball/31mets.html&cid Overrated? Not Zito, as Giants Blank Mets - New York Times Giants 3, Mets 0 Overrated? Not Zito, as Giants Blank Mets Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 31, 2007 The guy named Barry stepped into the batter’s box last night, and the booing started almost immediately. The chants came a few seconds later. “Overrated! Overrated!” the crowd screamed. Skip to next paragraph Barton Silverman/The New York Times Barry Zito improved to 5-5. He went seven innings and gave up six hits, a walk, struck out seven and lowered his E.R.A. to 4.21. Keep up with the latest news on the on The Times’s baseball blog. Go to the Bats Blog » Times Topics: The Yankees Times Topics: The Mets Barton Silverman/The New York Times Rich Aurilia was forced out on a ball hit by Barry Bonds in the third. David Wright, who had shifted near second, completed the double play. Sitting on the bench, might have chuckled. However briefly, the fans’ disdain rerouted toward one of his teammates. Barry Zito, the left-hander who spurned the ’ free-agent offer last off-season for $51 million more, a longer contract and the chance to continue living in Northern California, had apparently rankled some folks at Shea Stadium. Then Zito went out and produced a dominant pitching performance — seven scoreless innings in the Giants’ 3-0 victory — which probably bothered them even more. Overrated? Not last night. “Obviously, he was great,” Manager Willie Randolph said after the Mets were shut out for the first time this season. Almost in the next sentence, Randolph said the same thing about his left-handed control specialist, , who remained stuck at 295 career victories. He and Zito shared eerily similar pitching lines: Over seven innings, each threw 122 pitches, 77 for strikes, but the difference came in how they handled runners on base. Zito (5-5) stranded all six base runners, while Glavine, a pitch away from ending the inning each time the Giants scored, allowed them to rally with two outs and no one on base. He allowed two runs in the first and one in the third — Pedro Feliz drove in all three — then, buoyed by an extra day’s rest, stayed in long enough to hope the offense would awaken. It never did. “When their guys are hitting ground balls, I’m doing my job,” said Glavine, who scattered nine hits. “I’m just not getting the results. There’s nothing I can say to make people understand when you go out there, do what you want to do, make the pitches and you don’t get the results. It’s one of the single most frustrating things.” In 12 starts, Glavine has five victories and a 3.44 earned run average. He acknowledged afterward that considering the way he has pitched this season, he might have expected another victory here or there. But, he added, he understands that things have a way of evening out. “Three hundred is so far away right now that it’s not even part of the equation,” Glavine said. Unlike in their last meeting, Glavine kept Bonds in the park, holding him to one hit in four plate appearances. Bonds singled, grounded into a double play, was walked intentionally and grounded out, and his single contributed to the Giants’ two-run first. After falling behind, 1-2, Bengie Molina drew a walk, loading the bases for Feliz, who grounded a two-run single past In all, Glavine needed 30 pitches to set down the Giants, continuing an unsettling trend. He has not pitched a scoreless first inning since May 8, in San Francisco, and he threw more than 29 pitches in the first for the third consecutive start. “More than anything else, it’s a streak of bad luck,” Glavine said. “I’m going to give up runs at some point, they’ve just been coming too soon.” With Zito pitching, any runs were too much. On a glorious 76-degree day, Zito strolled into the Giants’ clubhouse before the game wearing a knit cap and a fleece jacket. The attire had no effect on his mood. Cool, calm and collected as always, Zito won his second start against the Mets this month and, a few players said, looked even better this time around. When he missed, he missed down. He complemented a fastball that did not exceed 87 miles an hour with a slow curve, a slower curve and an even slower curve. Of his seven strikeouts, six came on a curveball, and Mets hitters could not adjust when he jammed them with cutters. “He’s got this late movement,” said , who had one of the Mets’ six hits. The Mets put runners on base in each of the first five innings, including the first two batters in the second, then wasted Paul Lo Duca’s leadoff double (his 1,000th career hit) in the seventh. Zito finished off his evening by striking out pinch-hitter Julio Franco looking at a menacing 66-m.p.h curveball. “It’s always great coming to New York,” said Zito, who, as a member of the , pitched nine times at Yankee Stadium. “You get all these trash-talking fans saying everything they can think of to me in the outfield. That’s what makes this place special.” Asked if heard anything original, Zito said: “Not creative at all. Just blatant expletives at me. That’s all.” Staying true to his pregame promise, Willie Randolph inserted Guillermo Mota, fresh off his 50-game suspension for violating baseball’s policy on performance-enhancing drugs. He received a mixed reaction from the crowd of 41,395, although the fans clapped and welcomed him into the dugout after he pitched an uneventful eighth inning. Mota pitched a perfect ninth, too. “It’s nice to be back,” Mota said. ... On May 17, when Moises Alou was placed on the disabled list with a strained left quadriceps, he vowed to return May 28, the first day he was eligible to come off. That day has come and gone, and Alou said he was frustrated that the injury had taken longer than expected to heal. “I guess what I did was more serious than what we thought,” Alou said. “It’s something that I thought wouldn’t take that long, and I don’t know what set me back.” The earlier projection that Alou could return by the weekend seems a little premature, he said, and a more reasonable guess is that he will be activated toward the middle of next week. Alou was more optimistic about his pending return Sunday in Florida, but he tried running Monday and still felt discomfort. Next Article in Sports (3 of 26) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. METS NOTEBOOK; Bonds Sits One Out as the Beat Goes On METS 5, GIANTS 4; Down to Last Out, the Mets Aren&#8217;t Down at All Mets&#8217; Lineup Is Preparing for Mastery and Mystery METS 6, MARLINS 4; Sosa Rebounds as Mets Sweep Marlins Next Article in Sports (3 of 26) &#x00bb; $15 million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: Explore the most luxurious homes in the U.S. Virgin Islands Explore the most luxurious homes in Hawaii Explore the most luxurious homes in France Mets Win World Series - 1986 Home & Garden &#x00bb; Art & Design &#x00bb; Sarkozys: The French Kennedys? Phil Spector’s Long and Winding Road The Dirty Water Underground An Animated Film by Jeff Scher Artist Sets Up House(s) at the Grand Palais The New York Times Company
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-3&fd=R&url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,21830348-11088,00.html&cid=1116760279&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Hewitt overcomes Gaudio | Herald Sun Welcome to Herald Sun. Send a Letter to the Editor Corporate Photo Sales, Copyright Herald Sun Cartoons & Caricatures Memorabilia & Limited Editions Back Issues & Home Delivery Herald Sun - Sell your car for FREE Place a classified newspaper ad June 01, 2007 12:00am A LINESWOMAN'S error almost led to the unravelling of Lleyton Hewitt last night, before his fighting nature helped rescue his French Open campaign. Hewitt prevailed in five sets, beating 2004 French Open champion, Argentine Gaston Gaudio, 4-6 3-6 6-2 6-4 6-2 in more than 3 1/2 hours. It was another match Hewitt can add to his lengthening list of gritty claycourt performances where he has fought back against adversity. This time the setback came when the first set took an awkward deviation on the strength of a lineswoman's incorrect call. Gaudio was serving at 30-30 in the seventh game when Hewitt's forehand was wrongly called out. The Australian 14th seed had set the point up beautifully, working Gaudio to a section of court where he would be unable to counter Hewitt's return. However the lineswoman called the ball out, giving Gaudio a lucky reprieve. The error cost Hewitt a break point in a match that was waiting for somebody to falter. Chair umpire Pascal Maria did not need to cross the court fuly before he turned and reversed the call, ordering the point to be replayed. On the replayed point, Gaudio struck the net cord but the ball toppled over, giving him game point, which he converted. The frustration of such a missed opportunity temporarily side-tracked Hewitt. Serving in the next game, he fell behind 15-40 before surrendering the game at 30-40 when he found the net to give Gaudio the break. As is his way, Hewitt immediately turned and attended to his racquet strings, bottling the frustration inside. But it certainly affected him. Gaudio held serve to take the set 6-4 and broke Hewitt in the first service game of the second, going on to take the set 6-3. While he appeared no different in manner, Hewitt was obviously still trying to sort out his demons. It was a major turnaround. Both had slugged back and forth early on, feeling their way, and at times Hewitt had threatened to crack as the passionate Gaudio took to screaming at himself, as early as the fourth game. But the frustrations eroded just enough of Hewitt's concentration to open the door for the Argentine. Now a set up and with a break in the second, all the running was with Gaudio. It wasn't until Hewitt broke for the first time in the third game of the third set that his fire returned. While Hewitt suddenly carried himself differently, Gaudio double-faulted four times, failed to reach even a break point and generally walked like a schoolboy kicking stones. By the time the set was over, Hewitt had broken him again, and when Gaudio double-faulted to drop the opening game of the fourth, the door was not only open, Hewitt was leading the band through. Freo angry over TV promo Viduka catches Magpie eyes Cup hopes rest on Larkham Laing star in Lachal Hurdle Prop with Storm until 2010 Roche keen to help Hewitt T-Birds to test leader Fed: I could hardly see the ball Ullrich's Sydney Olympic smear Healy: What's new, Pussycats? Malthouse: commit or scrap Origin Friday Debate with Damian Barrett Search for more stories on this topic on , our news archive service. Custom built PC's - Buy a Dell PC tailored to your needs and only pay for what you want 1st mth best package + install 4 NOTHING*. Love & Relationships - Find a date near you on Match.com - # 1 Online Dating site Worldwide. It won't just be another day at the office. See the full demo. Receive our News Feeds Get your Newspaper Delivered Receive our Email Newsletter Send us your news photos Send us your story tips Get your Newspaper Delivered &copy; He