http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/12-4&fd=R&url=http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/baseball/317953_mari31.html&cid=1116777936&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Usual suspect does in M's Skip ads and navigation Last updated May 30, 2007 11:51 p.m. PT Usual suspect does in M's Guerrero's three-run homer off Hernandez sparks Angels' victory ANAHEIM, Calif. -- The Mariners wanted nothing more than to walk Vladimir Guerrero on Wednesday night. Orlando Cabrera wouldn't let them. Cabrera, who bats in front of Guerrero, went 3-for-4 with a walk, meaning the Mariners didn't have many opportunities to walk Guerrero, a man who pounds Seattle pitching. The Mariners battled back from an early 4-1 deficit to take a 5-4 lead in the fifth, but Felix Hernandez was about to discover the trouble with pitching to Guerrero. Hernandez had no choice once Reggie Willits and Cabrera reached base with none out. And Guerrero had no choice but to hit a three-run homer that was the pivotal blow in the Angels' 8-6 win. Whatever the Angels need against the Mariners, Guerrero gives them "Cabrera was the guy we had to get out, and we didn't," catcher Kenji Johjima said. "Because we didn't get him out, we had to face Guerrero." Guerrero is a good hitter at the worst of times. He's hitting .350 this year. But when you compare that number with what he's doing against Seattle -- 16-for-29, .552 this year -- Guerrero is in a slump against everybody else. "He's the best hitter I've ever faced," Hernandez said after the Mariners completed a 6-4 road trip, leaving them in second place, 5 1/2 games behind the Angels. "But I'm looking forward to seeing him again." The plan coming into the series was to walk Guerrero whenever possible. There were two intentional walks issued Tuesday, but for the most part Cabrera forced Seattle to pitch to Guerrero by collecting eight hits and two walks in 14 trips to the plate during the series. "We kept throwing the ball up and out over the plate to him," manager Mike Hargrove said. "That hurt." It didn't hurt as much as Guerrero's homer. With that one swing, the Angels won two of three from the Mariners instead of losing two of three. It's a two-game swing in the standings; Seattle could have been 3 1/2 games behind. They started the trip five games back. "We went 6-4, so it was a good trip," Hargrove said. "Anytime you go on the road and you win more than you lose, it's a good trip. If we'd won tonight, it would have been a great trip." Hernandez said he felt good going into the game. But he had trouble keeping the ball down in the strike zone, and when he didn't the Angels made him pay. The first indication of trouble was Gary Matthews Jr.'s three-run homer in the first, which was followed by a Casey Kotchman homer for a quick 4-1 Angels lead. The Mariners, who finished with 10 hits, clawed their way back with two runs in the fourth, but they left the bases loaded. They got two more in the fifth to take the lead and another in the sixth after Guerrero's homer, but that was the end of the line. Seattle, which has scored 98 of its 242 runs (40 percent) in the middle three innings, then shut down, getting just one base runner the rest of the night. That was DH Jose Vidro, who walked to open the ninth against closer Frankie Rodriguez. The Mariners brought the tying run to the plate three times, but they may as well have left their bats in the dugout. Rodriguez threw sliders in the dirt to Raul Ibanez, Jose Guillen and Ben Broussard, and all three went down swinging. The Mariners left Southern California disappointed but not distraught. One more win against the Angels would have made this a superb trip. But to win six of 10 in the middle of 23 games without a day off isn't shabby. And, hey, the Mariners are 23-17 against every team not named the Angels, and the Anaheim crew isn't on the schedule again until the final week of July, so the schedule is looking better. Maybe by then the Mariners will have come up with a way to get Guerrero out. Or, at least, shut Cabrera down. It was another nice night (69 degrees) in Southern California. STAR OF THE GAME: SS Orlando Cabrera went 3-for-4 with a walk and was in the middle of every Angels rally, forcing Seattle to pitch to the man who bats behind him, RF Vladimir Guerrero. PLAY OF THE GAME: Guerrero, who already had two singles, unloaded a three-run homer against RHP Felix Hernandez to lift the Angels from a 5-4 deficit to a 7-5 lead they never relinquished. Hernandez hadn't allowed a home run in 31 1/3 innings, but Wednesday the Angels tagged him for three, one each by CF Gary Matthews Jr., 1B Casey Kotchman and Guerrero. Matthews and Guerrero hit three-run shots. Hernandez wasn't at his best, giving up nine hits in six innings. RHP Sean Green let the Angels tack on a run before RHP Brandon Morrow took over. The Mariners came back from Tuesday's five-hit effort with 10 hits and six runs, but that proved insufficient as the Mariners didn't hit a single home run Wednesday against the three by the Angels. Kenji Johjima and 3B Adrian Beltre both had a couple of hits, and CF Ichiro Suzuki (23 games) and SS Yuniesky Betancourt (11 games) stretched out their hitting streaks. CF Matthews made a couple of well-above-average catches in center to keep the Mariners from scoring more than they did in the fourth and fifth. SS Betancourt was caught stealing on a hit-and-run to close out the fifth inning. 7:05 p.m., Safeco Field Add P-I Baseball headlines to Usual suspect does in M's Mariners Notebook: Shoulder improvement a relief for Ibanez Rainiers' Lehr in command Another impressive outing for Haren AL Notes: Twins push back Mauer's return NL Notes: Cardinals' Molina sidelined 4-6 weeks Angels fly by M's Mariners Notebook: M's up in air about whom they'll draft Jones' homers lead Rainiers Beckett picks up where he left off 'Stray-Rod?' Tabloid pounces on A-Rod A-Rod, Yankees snap 5-game losing streak Big Unit beats Phillies in return Guerrero's 3-run homer lifts Angels 8-6 Bedard throws down aces as Orioles win Add your voice to our most popular forum! Take part in our Mariners forum and talk about the team with other knowledgeable fanatics! Weaver will return to Seattle rotation next week. What's next for Weaver? Game playing in the outfield Reader blog: Mariner Housewife Woman’s view of Seattle baseball It's On Like Donkey Kong Babe Felix... I Like It. Economy nearly stalled in first quarter TB patient in Denver for treatment N.H. governor signs civil unions law Iraq suicide blast leaves up to 25 dead Putin: U.S. has triggered new arms race Listener helps save ailing disc jockey Wal-Mart cashier: I was fired for joking Promotional fax mistaken for bomb threat Musician canned for focus on wrong organ Couple sue Wal-Mart over slip in vomit New breed of cat retails for $22,000 Dying vet planned a final mission 'Spam King' suspect seized Recent grads offer real-world perspective to Class of 2007 Pre-Draft Notebook: Halperin says 'no' to Sonics Microsoft Surface brings computing to the table Ancestry.com puts 90M war records online New breed of cat retails for $22,000 Where car thieves love to tread Dying vet planned a final mission A city with no Sonics: How life will change if NBA leaves Seattle Viaduct-free plan on the table $6 tolls proposed for new 520 Bridge Where car thieves love to tread Condo dwellers seek quieter life in new parts of city 101 Elliott Ave. W. Home Delivery: (206) 464-2121 or (800) 542-0820 seattlepi.com serves about 1.7 million unique visitors and 30 million page views each month. Send investigative tips to
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-2&fd=R&url=http://www.ohio.com/mld/beaconjournal/17301891.htm&cid=1116832398&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Beacon Journal | 05/30/2007 | Indians batter Red Sox pitcher Thursday, May 31, 2007 Posted on Wed, May. 30, 2007 reprint or license this Indians batter Red Sox pitcher Byrd fares better than Matsuzaka, as Tribe unloads on Boston's vaunted starter It was Daisuke Matsuzaka night at Fenway Park, and the Indians couldn't have been more pleased. Red Sox Nation was counting on Matsuzaka to trigger a three-game sweep over the visitors from Cleveland. After all, he was the centerpiece of General Manager Theo Epstein's winter shopping spree and came into the game with a 7-2 record. Besides, the Red Sox -- and moreso their fans -- have a certain sense of entitlement: The thinking goes, ``Matsuzaka vs. Paul Byrd? Who are you kidding?'' But things don't always go according to form. It took the Indians the better part of six innings, but in the end, they dismembered Matsuzaka and left town with an 8-4 win. ``I think there was a little something extra for me to stop the slide,'' Byrd said. ``We're in first place, and there's a team one or two games behind us. So it's extra pressure, but that's why I came here.'' The Tribe lost two series on its nine-game trip to Kansas City, Detroit and Boston and still returned home with a 5-4 record, thanks to winning all three from the Tigers. ``These guys really played their tails off the whole trip,'' manager Eric Wedge said. ``We played pretty good baseball, even here. Boston just beat us the first two games.'' Byrd (6-1, 3.57 ERA) stopped the Sox's vaunted lineup cold for six innings, allowing one earned run (two total) and six hits. But in the seventh, he was stung for three consecutive singles and left with the bases loaded and nobody out. But even though the top of the lineup was set to face Byrd's replacement, Tom Mastny, the Sox failed to score. Mastny retired Coco Crisp and Kevin Youkilis, and Aaron Fultz induced David Ortiz to hit a semi line drive to Casey Blake at third. ``I would have liked to get through the seventh to give the bullpen a break,'' Byrd said. ``But it just wasn't in the cards.'' Byrd threw only 77 pitches and ran his string of walkless innings to 43. It helped that he threw first-pitch strikes to 25 of the 27 batters he faced. ``I take a lot of pride in making guys earn they way to first base,'' Byrd said. ``I'm not concerned with a personal streak. ``And the streak might have ended (in the fifth) against David Ortiz. There were two outs, and I threw the first pitch off the plate, but he swung and popped it up. If I had gone 2-and-0, I probably would have walked him.'' For four innings, Matsuzaka almost looked like a $103 million pitcher, the total paid by the Red Sox in salary and compensation to his former team in Japan. But Tribe batsmen saw enough pitches over that span to figure something out. And in the fifth and sixth innings, Matsuzaka looked more like a guy who should be earning the major- league minimum. Even before the Indians struck for their first two runs in the fifth, Matsuzaka got himself into and out of trouble. His most serious jam came in the first inning, when the Tribe loaded the bases (usually a bad sign) with one out, and Trot Nixon bounced into a double play. Matsuzaka's fortunes began to wane in the fifth. Kelly Shoppach kick-started the offense with a one-out single and stopped at third on Grady Sizemore's double. Casey Blake's ground out to short was enough to score Shoppach, and Travis Hafner's double brought Sizemore around. ``Matsuzaka really threw everything from the outset,'' Wedge said. ``We needed to see that. Once we did, we made some adjustments. I'm not going to tell you guys what they were.'' Things went south for Matsuzaka (7-3, 4.83 ERA) in the sixth. Even with a base-running mistake by Josh Barfield, he gave up four runs on five hits in the sixth inning. Included in the barrage were doubles by Nixon and David Dellucci, plus a two-run homer by Sizemore. In the middle of the rally, Barfield singled home Dellucci and advanced to second on Shoppach's second single of the game. But Barfield rounded second, and Manny Ramirez threw him out before he could get back to the bag. Except he didn't. Replays were conclusive in showing that second baseman Dustin Pedroia missed the tag, something that umpire Rick Reed didn't notice. Matsuzaka, who left after Sizemore's homer, was charged with six runs, 12 hits -- including six for extra bases -- and no walks. The 12 hits allowed are a Red Sox season high (Curt Schilling also gave up 12). ``He wasn't locating like he can, like he has, like he will,'' Sox manager Terry Francona said. Shoppach had four hits, including a home run, and Hafner doubled twice and singled, which might be a sign that he is finally emerging from his lengthy slump. According to Shoppach, there was no secret formula to making Matsuzaka a victim. ``We deserve a little credit for hitting a tough pitcher and getting him out of there a little early,'' he said. ``You just put your nose in there and get some hits.'' Sheldon Ocker can be reached at About the Real Cities Network Terms of Use & Privacy Statement
