http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-5&fd=R&url=http://www.thestar.com/Sports/article/219830&cid=1116812502&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ TheStar.com - Sports - A-Rod infuriates Jays as Yanks avoid sweep Full Text Article Archive TheStar.com - Sports - A-Rod infuriates Jays as Yanks avoid sweep A-Rod infuriates Jays as Yanks avoid sweep Toronto's Howie Clark misses a pop fly hit by New York's Jorge Posada in the ninth inning of a 10-5 Yankees win on Wednesday, May 30, 2007. As New York's Alex Rodriguez ran past Clark on the basepath, he yelled something that caused Clark to think he was being called off the play by shortstop John McDonald. The ball fell in and a run scored. Blue Jays stats, more Blue Jays 2007 schedule Photo gallery: Spring training Video: Jays fielding drills Shout leads to botched fielding play by Clark May 31, 2007 04:30 AM The Yankees left Toronto as victors. But that might be slim comfort as the team's biggest star heads out with his reputation in tatters after an on-field incident last night everyone connected with the Jays say is a first in their experience. With two out in the ninth and the Yankees on their way to a 10-5 win, Jorge Posada launched a sky-high pop-up. As substitute Jays third baseman Howie Clark settled under the ball, Alex Rodriguez ran past him on the basepath. Video replays clearly showed Rodriguez yelling something that was variously described by Jays on the field at the time as "Mine!" or "I got it!" Clark thought he was being called off by shortstop John McDonald. So he stepped out of the way and it fell in as another run scored. "I was under the fly ball and I thought I was called off ... and I let it drop. I heard a `Mine!' call," Clark said. Rodriguez admitted yelling, but denied calling for the ball. "I just said, `Ha!' ... that's it." Asked if he said, `Mine' or `Got it,' Rodriguez said, "I would never say that, that's not true. Basically guys, I could care less (what the Jays think). They have their opinions and we're looking at not getting swept. It was nothing personal. But I couldn't care less. My (teammates) in here think it's good." Rodriguez, earlier in the day, had to deal with a allegation that he had been spotted at a hotel and a Toronto strip club with a "mystery blonde." Rodriguez is married. After the controversial play, Jays manager John Gibbons stepped on the field to discuss it with the umpires. Distracting a fielder with a shout is a grey area in baseball, a no-no enforced by sportsmanship rather than the rulebook. "One of the reasons (the Yankees) are so respected is they've got a lot of pride, they do things right," Gibbons said, almost sadly. "That's not Yankee pride right there. I thought it was bush league. But it worked." "I don't know how to feel," Yankees manager Joe Torre said. "It's the game of baseball. It's not like he said, `I got it.' He didn't say that. He made a noise." The Yankees superstar seemed unabashed after the play, pushing away third base umpire Chad Fairchild as the official seemed to chide him. Rodriguez stood on third wearing a slight grin. "I don't get angry all that much," McDonald said, clearly biting his lip. "I don't remember a situation like that happening before." The Jays had battled gamely to climb back into the fray after going down five runs in the first. Rookie Jesse Litsch was rocked early and often and Gibbons yanked him after only two-thirds of an inning and five runs. Today, Litsch returns to Double-A New Hampshire to make way for Roy Halladay, who returns from injury against the visiting White Sox. Conrad Black on trial Great home delivery subscription deals here! More in the news Hamilton home for Preds? TFC player search is fraught with peril It's a numbers game for TFC striker Yankees 10, Blue Jays 5 A-Rod's affairs are none of our business Early bird Bishop set to bid for No.1 spot Dump-and-chase game makes for dull hockey Don Cherry takes his plaid to U.S. Hewitt rallies into third round at French Open Bryant asks for trade - then backs off MOST POPULAR ON THESTAR.COM Horoscopes for Thursday, May 31 Woman bounced from Montreal gay bar Stefani makes a clean getaway at the ACC Don Cherry takes his plaid to U.S. Crisp and buttery oatcakes Home of the million-dollar tuneup Ho Sang to receive the Gomez Award Woman bounced from Montreal gay bar Careers at the Star Pages of the Past Star Store & Photo Sales &copy; Copyright Toronto Star 1996-2007
