e to make a start-up league successful," he said. "On the surface, if history tells us anything, it can't possibly work," Carter added. "But -- this is going to sound like Yogi Berra -- history was a long time ago and now the landscape has changed. The right people properly capitalized should never be taken for granted." Success for the UFL may not mean long-term existence as a league, but a place for some of its teams as expansion members in the NFL, Carter said. &copy; Reuters 2007. All rights reserved. Editors Choice: Best pictures from the last 24 hours. START News Content Page Tags 'Text' | 'Picture' | 'Slideshow' | 'Video' ie. headline for article ie. headline for article END News Content Page Tags In quotes: Subprime fallout Spain sues to block U.S. claim to sunken treasure Bush envisions U.S. presence in Iraq like S.Korea Europe central banks to miss gold sale quota again Wachovia to buy A.G. Edwards for $6.8 billion Foot Locker no longer pursuing Genesco Western-Giant deal to proceed unless court acts Top Company Research Reports on Reuters.com Qantas Airways Ltd. [QAN] Globalstar IPO Update [GSAT] MFS Research Bond Fund [MRBFX] Reuters in Second Life Reuters is the world's largest international multimedia news agency, providing investing news, world news, business news, technology news, headline news, small business news, news alerts, personal finance, stock market, and mutual funds information available on Reuters.com, video, mobile, and interactive television platforms. Reuters journalists are subject to the Reuters Editorial Handbook which requires fair presentation and disclosure of relevant interests. START OF SmartSource Data Collector TAG Copyright (c) 1996-2006 WebTrends Inc. All rights reserved. END OF SmartSource Data Collector TAG
http://www.smh.com.au/news/tennis/hewitt-climbs-off-canvas/2007/06/01/1180205436456.html&cid Hewitt climbs off the canvas again - Tennis - Sport - smh.com.au Welcome to The Sydney Morning Herald. Hewitt climbs off the canvas again Back from the red &#133; Lleyton Hewitt celebrates after his gritty come-from-behind win against Gaston Gaudio at Roland Garros. PARIS: A trademark Lleyton Hewitt fightback put the Australian into the third round of the French Open with victory over 2004 champion Gaston Gaudio. No.14 seed Hewitt relishes a dogfight and he got just that on Thursday, heaving himself up from two-sets-to-love down to beat the Argentine 4-6, 3-6, 6-2, 6-4, 6-2 in three hours and 28 minutes. He next meets Finnish No.20 seed Jarkko Nieminen, who beat Frenchman Mathieu Montcourt in straight sets. Hewitt had looked down for the count after Gaudio established his dominance early in the match. The world No.72 converted the second of two break points in the ninth game of the first set to take a 5-4 lead and claimed the opener on his own serve with a smash. Gaudio kept the momentum, breaking Hewitt in the opening game of the second set when the Australian hit a backhand wide, charging on to eventually take a two-sets-to-love lead. Hewitt then dragged himself back into the match in the third game of the third set when Gaudio handed him a break with a double fault. It was all he needed to spark a remarkable resurgence. The 26-year-old baseliner went on to convert the second of two break points against Gaudio in the seventh game with a sharp return and Hewitt closed out the set with a backhand that shot past his opponent. Two double faults by Gaudio in the opening game of the fourth set gave Hewitt an early break. Hewitt's famed calls of "C'mon!" had barely been audible to that point, but when he saved break point in the second game, the volume increased markedly. He sent down a 205kmh bullet for set point and levelled at two sets all with a forehand down the line. Hewitt broke Gaudio in the opening game of the decider when the former world No.5 sent a backhand long and the Australian won his next service game to love with an ace. Hewitt broke Gaudio again in the fifth game and again won his service game to love before serving for the match. He brought up three match points with an ace and converted the first when Gaudio sent a forehand long. In other second-round matches No.16 seed Marcos Baghdatis beat Kristian Pless 7-5, 6-3, 6-4 while 20-year-old Serbian prodigy Novak Djokovic, the No.6 seed, beat Laurent Recouderc 6-3, 3-6, 6-3, 6-1. Meanwhile, top seed Roger Federer was furious with French Open officials who scheduled his second-round match to start and finish in the murky Paris gloom. The world No.1, who needs a Roland Garros title to complete the set of grand slams, rounded off his 6-1, 6-2, 7-6 (10-8) victory over French wildcard Thierry Ascione just before 9.15pm local time on Wednesday with Court Suzanne Lenglen in near-darkness. "When we shook hands, I told him I couldn't see him anymore it was so dark," Federer said. "The conditions were shocking. I know they want to get the matches over and done with, but what I don't like is that they know I'm the favourite and they think I should win in straight sets. 'Let's get Roger's match over and done with, then he's happy, he has a day off'. But what if it doesn't turn out this way? I would be very upset. I already wasn't happy playing so late. "I hate playing into dawn. I can hardly see the ball. You start stressing out. I can't believe other players were still playing after me because it was so dark." Federer was referring to France's Edouard Roger-Vasselin's five-set win over Radek Stepanek, which didn't finish until 9:30pm. The Swiss star said the situation reminded him of his heartbreaking semi-final defeat to Rafael Nadal in 2005, which was played in similar dismal conditions. On that occasion, Federer wanted the match called off for the day. "I wanted to stop that match, but there was pressure from the crowd, from television, from my opponent - and if you don't agree with your opponent, you're stupid." At one stage on Wednesday, Federer looked as if he would have the match wrapped up quickly as he raced to a two-set lead inside 48 minutes as the world No.168 was outclassed. But Federer wasted two match points in the ninth game of the third set and three more in the subsequent tie-breaker before he managed to move into the third round, where he faces Italy's Potito Starace. Federer, attempting to become the first man since Rod Laver in 1969 - and just the third man in history - to hold all four grand slam titles at the same time, was playing for the third day in a row after rain forced his first-round victory over America's Michael Russell to start on Monday and finish on Tuesday. But he showed no signs of fatigue, closing out the first set in 22 minutes, allowing Ascione just four points on his serve. send photos, videos & tip-offs to 0424 SMS SMH (+61 424 767 764), or us. on home delivery of the Herald - subscribe today Hewitt climbs off the canvas again Back from the red &#133; Lleyton Hewitt celebrates after his gritty come-from-behind win against Gaston Gaudio at Roland Garros. Place a classified ad Copyright &#169; 2007. The Sydney Morning Herald. Browse for a Date Viduka set for Newcastle switch Olympian contests dishonesty charge Loss to Socceroos was 'humiliating' Brazilian targets A League top four for Phoenix debut McDonald keen to impress in Socceroos home debut Few surprises in SA squad Spurs crush Jazz to advance to NBA finals Stoner next king of MotoGP: Hayden Ducks flying high after 1-0 win over Senators Galaxy won't loan out Beckham Aussie skipper set for America's Cup challenge Home affordability is the worst in 20 years; should we give up on owning a home? Do the ends justify the means in reality show Rambo: The Senior Years Our resident artist imagines Sly Stallone in a retirement village. Lawson cedes his place 