http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/0-3&fd=R&url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/nba/lakers/2007-05-30-kobe-focus_N.htm&cid=1116735035&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Is Kobe Bryant trade bait, or a Laker for life? - USATODAY.com How do I find it? Buy and sell tickets to premium and sold out events Search by events or regions: Looking to sell tickets quick? Shaquille O'Neal and coach Phil Jackson have gone in-and-out of Kobe Bryant's career with the Lakers. Bryant's statistics with them: O'Neal (1996-97 to 1998-99) O'Neal and Jackson (1999-2000 to 2003-04) Jackson (2005-06 to 2006-07) Source: USA TODAY research TIMELINE: HOW KOBE, LAKERS GOT TO TRADE TALKS Two weeks after Kobe Bryant is drafted out of high school No. 13 overall by Charlotte, he is acquired in trade by Los Angeles Lakers GM Jerry West for Vlade Divac. Lakers sign free agent Shaquille O'Neal. Phil Jackson named Lakers head coach. With O'Neal and Bryant leading way, Jackson's Lakers win first of three consecutive NBA titles, beating Indiana 4-2. A short time later, West retires as GM and Mitch Kupchak takes over. With Bryant averaging 29.4 points in playoffs, Lakers beat Philadelphia 4-1 for second consecutive title. Lakers sweep New Jersey to win third NBA title in row. Bryant averages career-high 32.1 points in playoffs, but Lakers fall to San Antonio in Western Conference semifinals. Bryant is arrested and charged with sexual assault alleged in June at Colorado resort. Last season together for Bryant, O'Neal and Jackson is filled with turmoil -- including ongoing distraction of Bryant's sexual-assault case where he often shuttled between Colorado court proceedings and Lakers games. Yet Lakers make it to NBA Finals before falling to Detroit 4-1. After season, Jackson resigns, O'Neal is traded to Miami and Bryant signs $136 million deal. Sexual-assault case against Bryant is dropped when prosecutor says accuser could not advance case. Accuser later files civil suit that is settled for undisclosed amount. Lakers, without Jackson and O'Neal, miss the playoffs for only second time in 29 years. Jackson returns as head coach of Lakers. Bryant averages 35.4 points, the NBA's best in nearly 20 years. Jan. 22 he scores 81 against Toronto, second all time to Wilt Chamberlain's 100. Lakers are eliminated in first round by Phoenix after leading 3-1. O'Neal's Miami Heat, meanwhile, win first NBA title. he didn't tell ESPN in recent interview that he wanted West back and in full control or he would ask to be traded. "I would love for him to be a part of this," Bryant says. "But it's not something where I demand he comes here. ... I love being a Laker. I want to retire a Laker. I want to fix this thing or at least help any way I can." Bryant becomes infuriated after quotes Lakers "insider" as saying it was Bryant's insistence on getting away from O'Neal that prompted O'Neal's trade to Miami. Bryant tells ESPN Radio, "I would like to be traded. ... Tough as it is to come to that conclusion, there's no other alternative." -- Bryant talks about meeting with owner Jerry Buss: "I went up to his penthouse suite. (Buss) looks me dead in the face and says, 'Kobe, I am not going to re-sign Shaq. I am not about to pay him $30 million a year or $80 million over three years. No way in hell. ... This is my decision. It's independent of you. My mind is made up. It doesn't matter to me what you do in free agency because I do not want to pay (Shaq).' " -- O'Neal responds to Bryant. "I believe Kobe 100%. Absolutely. There's no doubt in my mind Kobe is telling the truth. I believe him a thousand percent." -- Later Wednesday, after Bryant talks with Jackson, "I always dreamed about retiring as a Laker. I just hope and hope that something can be resolved. Something can be figured out. Just something so I can stay here." Is Kobe Bryant trade bait, or a Laker for life? By David DuPree, USA TODAY sent shockwaves through the NBA on Wednesday when he said in a radio interview he wanted to be traded from the Los Angeles Lakers. Reverberations continued even after the league's biggest star said later in another ESPN Radio interview he wanted to retire as a Laker. Audio of interview; Kobe's blog shows change of heart David DuPree assesses Kobe situation in chat transcript Bryant said the Lakers misled him about building an elite team and he no longer trusts them. On his website, he said he was frustrated by a newspaper report that said he was behind "That place is a mess," Bryant said, referring to the Lakers' front office. "If we're not making strides here to improve this team right now, to be aggressive in that nature, then what's the point of having me here? "I would like to be traded, yeah," continued Bryant, who has led the league in scoring the last two seasons. "Tough as it is to come to that conclusion, there's no other alternative. It's rough man, but I don't see how you can rebuild that trust." In response to Bryant's trade talks, Lakers owner Dr. Jerry Buss issued the following statement: "We are aware of the media reports. However, Kobe has not told us directly that he wants to be traded. We have made it very clear that we are building our team around Kobe and that we intend for him to be a Laker his entire career. "We will speak directly to Kobe, and until we do that, we will not comment publicly about this." The two sides have a lot to discuss, as Bryant seemed to allow room for reconciliation after talking to Lakers coach Phil Jackson. "When Phil and I spoke, he was optimistic and determined that we'll both be back," Bryant told ESPN Radio. "Phil is somebody I listen to. I lean on him a lot. He assured me things are going to be OK. Things are going to be all right. &#8230; Which was very encouraging. I don't want to go anywhere else. I want to be here for the rest of my career." Feelings built up for Bryant: 's best explanation of the roller-coaster-like ride he led the Los Angeles Lakers on begins with feeling betrayed by the team. Bryant wrote on his website that he became infuriated Tuesday when the Los Angeles Times quoted "a Lakers insider" saying it was Bryant's insistence on not wanting to play any longer with that prompted the center's trade to the Miami Heat. That report, combined with his feeling that the Lakers were not building a contender, led to him saying Wednesday he wanted to be traded. Hours later he said he hoped something could be worked out. The Lakers haven't made a major trade, had a significant free agent signing or scored a draft coup since the O'Neal trade. After winning 20 playoff series and three NBA championships from 2000 to 2004, they have won only four postseason games in the last three years. They finished seventh in the Western Conference the last two seasons and were eliminated by the Phoenix Suns in the first round of the playoffs both times. "Kobe is a very competitive guy and a team guy, but he wants to win," said Jack Ramsay, an ESPN analyst. "It would be a rarity for a team with that composition of players (Lakers current roster) to be a contending team. They're doing as well as they can by making the playoffs and taking Phoenix to seven games last year, which is commendable." Bryant wrote on his website Wednesday that Lakers owner Jerry Buss told him O'Neal was being traded for financial reasons and because of O'Neal's declining skills. Bryant was adamant that he had nothing to do with O'Neal's leaving and said he could no longer trust the team. "The more I thought about the future, the more I became convinced that the Lakers and me just have two different visions for the future," Bryant wrote. "The Lakers are pursuing a longer-term plan that is different from what Dr. Buss shared with me at the time I re-signed as a free agent. "I have seen that plan unfold for the last three years and watched great trade opportunities come and go and have seen free agents passed on. That has led to the Lakers not winning a playoff series. "All of that was frustrating in itself, but then this week to have someone 'inside' the Laker organization try to blame me in the media for us not being a contender right now &#8212; that is what brought me to my current position today." If Bryant, who turns 29 in August, goes on the trading block (he has a no-trade option in his contract, which means he can refuse any deal if it isn't to a team of his liking), it could cause a feeding frenzy. Ramsay says it's possible Bryant could still be traded. "I read in the Dallas paper Tuesday, the headline on the sports page was, 'Go for Kobe, and if it takes Dirk, it's worth it,' " Ramsay said. "That's a huge, huge statement. But I think teams will think in that direction. He's an amazing player, and there aren't any quite like him." Bryant was the only player in the league to average at least 30 points (31.6) and was an All-NBA first-team and NBA all-defensive first-team selection. Bryant has spent his entire 11-year NBA career with the Lakers. Only one active player, and his 12 seasons with the Minnesota Timberwolves, has a longer tenure with one team. Three significant issues face any team looking to acquire : salary-cap limitations, who they are willing to give up and what it would do to team chemistry. Here are five possible front-runners (in order of likelihood): &#8212; The Knicks need a star to return the thrill to Madison Square Garden. Money is no object, and they have the players to give up to make a deal work, such as center &#8212; The Bulls have plenty of young talent to offer, but they may have their sights set on the Minnesota Timberwolves' . They'll have salary cap space. Unwilling to part with small forward in a possible deal for , they may do it to get Bryant. Also to offer: shooting guard &#8212; Owner Mark Cuban is still smarting from the Mavericks' first-round ouster and may feel a need to get into the Kobe sweepstakes and keep MVP , though the Los Angeles Lakers would almost certainly demand him. A package of guard might pique the Lakers' interest. &#8212; Clearly rebuilding, the Bobcats have good young players (Raymond Felton, calling the shots, Bryant knows everything would be done to get the right pieces around him. &#8212; A homecoming might be attractive to Bryant. The 76ers, with three first-round picks in next month's draft and small forward and rising young star , have plenty of pieces to entice the Lakers. To report corrections and clarifications, contact Reader Editor By Robert Hanashiro, USA TODAY Bryant has been frustrated with the lack of talent surrounding him in Los Angeles since O'Neal was traded. The Lakers have not won a playoff series since and have not made any splashes through trades or free agency. In happier times, coach Phil Jackson, left, Shaquille O'Neal, center, and Kobe Bryant, right, led the Lakers to three consecutive NBA titles. Here, the trio is presented with their trophy by commissioner David Stern after sweeping the Nets in the 2002 finals. By Robert Deutsch, USA TODAY USA TODAY welcomes your thoughts, stories and information related to this article. Please stay on topic and be respectful of others. Keep the conversation appropriate for interested readers across the map. Newspaper Home Delivery - Subscribe Today Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Right Add USATODAY.com RSS feeds
