g date of June 30. The National Hockey League's free-agent window opens the very next day. Email to a friend Nashville has seven players set to become unrestricted free agents, including captain Kimmo Timonen and forwards Paul Kariya and Peter Forsberg. The NHL's board of governors still has to approve the sale, leaving players and agents in need of answers from the team and general manager David Poile. "I don't think the league wants David Poile to hit July 1 not knowing who his owner is and not knowing what direction it's going to go in," Timonen's agent, Bill Zito, said yesterday. "We have a 100-point team, and now, all of the sudden, it's going to disintegrate because of the timing of legalities? That doesn't make any sense." Poile and Leipold both declined interview requests yesterday. Poile was said to be awaiting direction. Rumours have swirled around the franchise since Balsillie's purchase agreement was announced last week. There has been talk the Predators could move to Winnipeg, Hamilton or to Balsillie's base near Waterloo -- talk that will likely continue despite NHL commissioner Gary Bettman's claim on Monday that it "is not going anywhere." "I know if I was a free agent thinking about signing that would be the first question I'd be asking," Nashville centre Jason Arnott told The Tennessean. The Predators were already going to face a challenge in resigning at least a couple of their marquee names, especially Timonen, who is primed for the largest payday of his career after registering at least 40 points for the fifth straight year. The 32-year-old defenceman made US$2.28-million last season, but is thought to be looking at the deal fellow defenceman Andrei Markov signed with the Montreal Canadiens on Monday as comparable. Markov signed a four-year contract reported to be worth US$23-million. Forsberg is also weighing his options. "He's had all these health issues for a couple of years," agent Don Baizley said yesterday. "And he's got to, first of all, find out whether they can be resolved to the point that he can play at the level he expects of himself. And I don't think that's a decision that he's going to make any time soon." Baizley did say his clients -- Forsberg and Kariya -- would also want to know about Nashville's situation. "I really think it's going to be business as usual," NHL player agent Allan Walsh said. "I don't feel that the sale is going to impact much on players' decisions to sign there, one way or the other. Management has been very stable and very consistent over the years and if you listen to what is being said on the NHL side, and on the ownership side, it does not appear that franchise move is imminent." John Mayer acts out a bizarre ... Privacy czar warns web users to be wary Students cruising online networking... Deaths may be linked to diabetes drug Health Canada says the deaths ... Fox Sports World Canada Copyright & Permission Rules &copy; 2007 CanWest Interactive, a division of CanWest MediaWorks Publications Inc. . All rights reserved. Unauthorized distribution, transmission or republication strictly prohibited.
http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi%3Ff%3D/c/a/2007/05/31/GIANTS.TMP&cid Giants rebound from tough loss Giants rebound from tough loss Henry Schulman, Chronicle Staff Writer Wednesday, May 30, 2007 (05-30) 20:43 PDT New York -- - You could argue from now until the next ice age whether Barry Zito was worth $126 million, but you cannot dispute that he was worth his weight in diamonds to the woebegone Giants on Wednesday night. One night after a loss that sucked the oxygen from their blood and the joy from their souls, the Giants needed a little nourishment and Zito gave them a seven-course feast. He blanked the New York Mets for seven innings, defining the term "stopper," in a 3-0 victory that ended his team's losing streak at four games. "It was awesome, outstanding," said shortstop Omar Vizquel, who contributed four excellent defensive plays. "I think he knew he needed to turn it on tonight and he did, in New York, against a good team. He wanted to show everybody out here what he was all about. It was a great outcome for him." Some pitchers say all wins are the same. Zito recognized this one was not, that after Tuesday's 12-inning balk-a-palooza he had to stand 11 feet high against 295-game winner Tom Glavine, because that is what an ace is supposed to do. "I take that seriously," Zito said. "In 2002 with Oakland I had a real good record after losses (13-1). That's something the team feeds off of. When we had a losing streak, the team could rely on me. It's an important role." Zito allowed six hits, walked one and struck out a season-high seven for his second consecutive victory and his second win against the Mets. He swore he does not want to pitch "with a vendetta against people," but here is a fact: Before the Giants sent the Brinks truck to Zito's driveway, he was negotiating with the Mets. A little birdie spread word that Zito no longer was an ace and no better than a middle-rotation starter, perhaps to drive his price down. Zito believed the birdie had "M-E-T-S" written across its chest. Commanding his curveball and rarely making Bengie Molina move his glove, Zito held Tuesday heroes Jose Reyes and Carlos Delgado hitless in five at-bats combined. No Met reached third base. After throwing 122 pitches, Zito gave way to Jack Taschner for a scoreless eighth, and Brad Hennessey fanned Delgado to start a perfect ninth for his third career save, a good audition should the Giants decide to try another closer. The vilified Armando Benitez was said to be unavailable with swelling in his right knee, which needed to be drained. Pedro Feliz drove in all three runs in rallies that began with two outs. He hit a bases-loaded single on a 3-2 pitch in the first inning that scored Rich Aurilia and Barry Bonds, who each had singled. In the third, Molina singled and scored from first on Feliz's triple off the center-field wall. Feliz had been 2-for-12 lifetime against Glavine. Feliz hit each ball when he was ahead in the count. Perhaps he is learning from Molina, who bats ahead of him and wears pitchers out. Molina saw eight pitches when he walked in the first inning to load the bases and 10 more when he singled in the third. "He is a grinder," manager Bruce Bochy said of his catcher. "He competes so well. He gets great at-bats and he never gives away at-bats. He battles all the time. We know about the clutch hits, and even when he doesn't get a hit, he knows how to build the count up and use all fields." Perhaps the best development for the Giants was Aurilia's 4-for-4 night, coming toward the end of what he described Tuesday as "one of the worst months I've had in a long time." He was 9-for-67 in May before facing Glavine. "I think I matched my last three-week total for hits tonight," Aurilia said. "I made a few adjustments in the cage before the game with the staff. There were a couple of things my teammates saw. It was great to actually implement it and have it work. Hopefully, I can keep it up." The team hopes Zito can keep it up, too. He has allowed one run in his last 14 innings to improve to 5-5. Vizquel faced Zito in the American League and was asked if the left-hander looks the same from behind now as he did when Vizquel used to face him from the batter's box. Vizquel thought for a second and said, "I see a bigger ass now." E-mail Henry Schulman at This article appeared on page Get up to 50% off home delivery of the Chronicle for 12 weeks! Man Described As a Top Spammer Arrested Sprawl clashes with warming in California Mo. Toddler Ruins Monks&#x27; Sand Design Gas station owner lowers price to $2.99 per gallon SAN FRANCISCO Officer called a &#x27;suspected&#x27; public danger New league looking to challenge the NFL Lara Is Not A Porn Star Or, How to make it in porn before you were even born Bush Declares Self &#x27;Mega Decider&#x27; New documents ensure Dubya will rule... Digging biodynamic Restaurateurs look beyond organic in quest to cultivate... Dull, dull, dull, dull South S.F. transit village is a nothing in several... Whales disappear -- rescuers believe they&#x27;re back at sea Kids&#x27; rooms grow up Cute gives way to sophisticated designs, rooms that... PENINSULA / Stanford impostor also fooled people at Santa Clara University... SAN FRANCISCO / Youth mentor, dad of 3, shot dead in North Beach His... Bill would simplify changing names for partners, men Current law makes it... Pass it on -- Norris wants to keep Aces&#x27; legacy alive Man Described As a Top Spammer Arrested Putin: Missile Tests Are Response to US N.H. Governor Signs Civil Unions Law Listener Helps Save Ailing Disc Jockey Judge Will Release Letters in Libby Case See more from this dealer View All Top Autos &copy; 2007 Hearst Communications Inc.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-3&fd=R&url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story%3Fid%3D2887465&cid=1116813826&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ ESPN.com: Mavs' Cuban hopes to create league to rival NFL Skip to the content Scouts Inc. Briefing Room 2007 NFL Draft order NFL Hall of Fame Mavs' owner Cuban says pro football demand is greater than supply Updated: May 31, 2007, 1:03 AM ET owner Mark Cuban is part of a group considering formation of a football league that would compete with the NFL for players drafted lower than the second round. The league, still very much in the preliminary stage, would play its games on Friday nights. The NFL does not play then because of the potential conflict with high school football. "It's a pretty simple concept," Cuban said in an e-mail to The Associated Press. "We think there is more demand for pro football than supply." It's a pretty simple concept. We think there is more demand for pro football than supply. The proposal was first disclosed by The New York Times on its Web site, which said it was the idea of Bill Hambrecht, a Wall Street investor who was a minority partner in the Oakland Invaders of the USFL, which played in the spring from 1983-85. Sharon Smith, a spokeswoman for Hambrecht and Company, had no comment and said Hambrecht was traveling and unavailable to talk about the idea. NFL spokesman Greg Aiello said he was aware of the proposed league, but had no further comment. On his blog, Cuban explained how the new league, dubbed the UFL, would actually be good for the NFL. "The NFL wants and needs competition," Cuban wrote. "They have grown so big and powerful that every move they make is scrutinized by local or federal officials. A competitor allows them to point to us and explain that their moves are for competitive reasons rather than the move of a monopoly." There have been numerous leagues that have tried to compete with the NFL and a few that actually played games, starting with the AFL, which began in 1960 and fully merged with the NFL a decade later. It included such current franchises as New England, Oakland, Kansas City, San Diego, Buffalo, the New York Jets and Denver. More recently came the World Football League in the early 1970s, which raided the NFL for such stars as Larry Csonka. Then came the USFL, which played in the spring before folding after receiving only $3 in an antitrust "victory" over the NFL. The USFL featured such future Hall of Famers as Jim Kelly, Reggie White and Steve Young, but lost millions of dollars trying to compete for players. It also had internal struggles among a majority of owners who wanted to stay in the spring, and the best known among them, Donald Trump, who wanted to move to the fall and try to force a merger with the NFL. The most recent pro football league was the XFL, founded by the World Wrestling Federation and televised by NBC. The XFL lasted just three months in the spring of 2001 and was best known for a player named Rod Smart, called "He Hate Me," who later played as a return man and backup running back in the NFL. So far, the proposed new league is in its infancy and Cuban is the only potential owner for what the founders hope will be an eight-team league. Cuban said in his e-mail he believes the salary cap makes it easier to compete financially with the NFL because of the salary imbalance that leaves lower-level players with lower salaries. That would allow the new league to fill its rosters with players taken lower than the second round, as well as late NFL cuts and free agents who escape the NFL draft. Many such players, including , a sixth-round pick of New England, have become NFL stars. "That's not to say it will be easy. It won't," Cuban wrote. "We still have to cover quite a bit of ground and have a lot of milestones to hit. That said, if we can get the right owners I obviously think we can make this work." The Associated Press contributed to this report. "Mavs' owner Cuban says pro football demand is greater than supply" Sources: Evidence warrants indictment of Vick Fins' Porter pays fine for punching Bengals' Jones Broncos' Kircus 'confident' he'll be cleared in fight Ex-NFL players getting aid for Alzheimer's rising Jersey change too costly for Raiders WR Porter Changes to the CBA and a larger salary cap are two reasons that players such as Justin McCareins probably won't be June 1 cuts. Chicago will not regret the decision to play Devin Hester at wide receiver next season. Check out our new NFL blog, Haskmarks, your one-stop source for news, notes and anecdotes about the NFL. Michael Vick and Pacman Jones don't have to abandon their friends. They just need to assume more control over them. We've always admired coaches who ignore their families and think only about winning. But the grind has become so harsh that some are wondering if it's worth it. Robin Kiffin, wife to Monte, mom to Lane, has shared her guys with football for decades. She's learned a thing or two about keeping coaches close to home.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-6&fd=R&url=http://news10now.com/content/all_news/%3FArID%3D107232%26SecID%3D83&cid=1116829994&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ News 10 Now | 24 Hour Local News | ALL NEWS Senate expected to approve bill lifting restrictions on ticket scalping Updated: 5/31/2007 8:18 AM Ticket scalping could soon become an easier process in the state of New York. The senate is expected approve a bill that would lift long-time restrictions on reselling tickets to sporting events, concerts and shows. The state Assembly has already voted for the bill, which could be signed into law tomorrow, when the state's old anti-scalping law expires. Under the proposed rules, the state would stop capping prices for tickets sold on the secondary market. Scalpers would still be banned from selling tickets within 1,500 feet of large arenas. But for the first time, it would be entirely legal for average fans to scalp their seats on the Internet. Email this Story to a Friend --Select An Event Type-- Judge rules student records be released in teacher abuse case... Car chase suspect talks... Arcuri to host public power meetings... Putting an end to text message spam... Copyright &copy;2007 TWEAN News Channel of Syracuse, LLC, d/b/a News 10 Now.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/memphis/Content%3Foid%3Doid%253A29191&cid=1116821789&ei=m-xeRubsBY2G0gGY99jYDQ Grizzlies Hire Iavaroni As New Coach :: The Memphis Flyer :: the mid-south's news weekly :: Sports Buzz :: Sports & Activities May 31 - Jun 6, 2007 Beale Street Music Festival
http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi%3Ff%3D/c/a/2007/05/31/FOOTBALL.TMP&cid New league looking to challenge the NFL New league looking to challenge the NFL Verne Kopytoff, Chronicle Staff Writer Thursday, May 31, 2007 A rival to the National Football League, funded by prominent San Francisco investment banker Bill Hambrecht and Google Inc. executive Tim Armstrong, is being planned for next summer, according to a spokeswoman for Hambrecht. The United Football League hopes to field teams in eight cities that have no NFL franchises, including Las Vegas, Los Angeles and Mexico City. The founders are counting on fan support and a cable television deal to make the league profitable after five years. Mark Cuban, the billionaire owner of the Dallas Mavericks basketball team, already has signed on as team owner, according to a report Wednesday in the New York Times. But taking on the NFL, among the most popular leagues in professional sports and a television ratings juggernaut, is risky. A number of upstarts have tried and failed, such as the XFL, which folded in 2001 after one season, the United States Football League, which finished the last of its three seasons in 1985, and the World Football League, which survived two seasons in the 1970s. "The odds are against any competitive league that goes up against the NFL," said Dan Rascher, associate professor of sports management at the University of San Francisco. "Maybe if they play in the off-season -- there's plenty of football fans who want to see football 12 months a year." Hambrecht and Armstrong were unavailable for comment. The NFL declined a request for an interview. The new league is still in the early planning stages and is without players, coaches or much of an executive staff beyond two dot-com entrepreneurs who previously worked for the National Basketball Association. The likelihood of a UFL team in the Bay Area is remote, given that there already are two established NFL franchises in the area to compete against -- the Oakland Raiders and the San Francisco 49ers. Aside from Cuban, who is known for his bombast and iconoclastic business sense, no other owners are lined up for the league. Boone Pickens, a Texas billionaire, had intended to buy a team but recently pulled out, according to the Times. Owners would pay $30 million for an initial half-interest in a team, and the league would own the other half. Teams later would sell shares to the public in an effort to raise an additional $60 million per franchise. Star players, who demand multi-million-dollar salaries, are not likely to be recruited by the new league. Rather, lower tier players, including those cut from the NFL, will fill the ranks and be paid lower salaries. Rascher supported the new league's strategy to target cities without NFL teams, saying that many large markets with existing stadiums are hungry for football. Keeping ticket prices low may lure fans who are loathe to pay for the NFL's pricier seats. The New York Times first reported about the new league Wednesday. A Hambrecht spokeswoman confirmed that the article was accurate. Hambrecht is the founder and chief executive of WR Hambrecht + Co, an investment bank known for championing initial public offerings that are priced in an auction rather than in back-room deals. He also was a minority investor in the USFL's Oakland Invaders until the league shut. Armstrong is president of Google's advertising sales in North America and recently invested in a professional lacrosse franchise in Boston. Both men have pledged $2 million for the league. In doing so, they join a long list of successful businessmen who have tried their hands at professional sports, including Cuban and Oracle's Larry Ellison, who races yachts. Arena Football is now the only challenger to the NFL, and only to a limited extent. The upstart league, which plays in arenas that have a much smaller capacity than stadiums, fields eight-man teams and hold its season in the spring, so it doesn't compete with the NFL. This article appeared on page Get up to 50% off home delivery of the Chronicle for 12 weeks! Man Described As a Top Spammer Arrested Sprawl clashes with warming in California Mo. Toddler Ruins Monks&#x27; Sand Design Gas station owner lowers price to $2.99 per gallon SAN FRANCISCO Officer called a &#x27;suspected&#x27; public danger New league looking to challenge the NFL Lara Is Not A Porn Star Or, How to make it in porn before you were even born Bush Declares Self &#x27;Mega Decider&#x27; New documents ensure Dubya will rule... Digging biodynamic Restaurateurs look beyond organic in quest to cultivate... Dull, dull, dull, dull South S.F. transit village is a nothing in several... Whales disappear -- rescuers believe they&#x27;re back at sea Kids&#x27; rooms grow up Cute gives way to sophisticated designs, rooms that... PENINSULA / Stanford impostor also fooled people at Santa Clara University... SAN FRANCISCO / Youth mentor, dad of 3, shot dead in North Beach His... Bill would simplify changing names for partners, men Current law makes it... Pass it on -- Norris wants to keep Aces&#x27; legacy alive Man Described As a Top Spammer Arrested Putin: Missile Tests Are Response to US N.H. Governor Signs Civil Unions Law Listener Helps Save Ailing Disc Jockey Judge Will Release Letters in Libby Case See more from this dealer View All Top Autos &copy; 2007 Hearst Communications Inc.
